INSERT INTO "BankQuestion" ("id","skillId","subareaKey","concept","difficulty","type","questionEn","questionPl","optionsEn","optionsPl","correctIndex","acceptedAnswers","orderItems","correctOrder","explanationEn","explanationPl","theoryEn","theoryPl","xp","qualityState","model") VALUES ('bank-speaking-structure-1','speaking','speaking:structure','speaking-structure-1','beginner','mcq','You have ten minutes to give a talk on switching to a four-day work week. Which overall structure will be clearest for your audience?','You have ten minutes to give a talk on switching to a four-day work week. Which overall structure will be clearest for your audience?',ARRAY['Open by previewing your main points, deliver them in order, then summarize what you covered','List every fact you know in the order you happened to learn them','Start with your conclusion, then read your reference list aloud','Improvise freely and trust the audience to find the thread']::text[],ARRAY['Open by previewing your main points, deliver them in order, then summarize what you covered','List every fact you know in the order you happened to learn them','Start with your conclusion, then read your reference list aloud','Improvise freely and trust the audience to find the thread']::text[],0,ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::int[],'Telling the audience what you''ll cover, covering it, then recapping gives listeners a roadmap that makes the content easy to follow and remember.','Telling the audience what you''ll cover, covering it, then recapping gives listeners a roadmap that makes the content easy to follow and remember.','A classic talk structure has a clear beginning, middle, and end: preview your key points, develop them one at a time, then summarize. Listeners cannot rewind a live talk, so this repetition helps them follow and retain the message. The structure also keeps you on track and prevents rambling.','A classic talk structure has a clear beginning, middle, and end: preview your key points, develop them one at a time, then summarize. Listeners cannot rewind a live talk, so this repetition helps them follow and retain the message. The structure also keeps you on track and prevents rambling.',10,'approved','curated-taste');
INSERT INTO "BankQuestion" ("id","skillId","subareaKey","concept","difficulty","type","questionEn","questionPl","optionsEn","optionsPl","correctIndex","acceptedAnswers","orderItems","correctOrder","explanationEn","explanationPl","theoryEn","theoryPl","xp","qualityState","model") VALUES ('bank-speaking-structure-2','speaking','speaking:structure','speaking-structure-2','intermediate','mcq','Midway through a presentation you want listeners to clearly notice that you are moving from describing a problem to proposing solutions. What is the most effective technique?','Midway through a presentation you want listeners to clearly notice that you are moving from describing a problem to proposing solutions. What is the most effective technique?',ARRAY['Use a verbal signpost such as ''Now that we''ve seen the problem, let''s look at three ways to fix it''','Lower your voice and hope people infer the shift','Add a new slide with no spoken transition','Speed up so you can reach the solutions faster']::text[],ARRAY['Use a verbal signpost such as ''Now that we''ve seen the problem, let''s look at three ways to fix it''','Lower your voice and hope people infer the shift','Add a new slide with no spoken transition','Speed up so you can reach the solutions faster']::text[],0,ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::int[],'An explicit signpost tells the audience where you are in the talk and what is coming next, keeping them oriented through the transition.','An explicit signpost tells the audience where you are in the talk and what is coming next, keeping them oriented through the transition.','Signposting uses transition phrases like ''first'', ''on the other hand'', and ''to sum up'' to mark the boundaries between sections of a talk. Because audiences cannot see your outline, these verbal cues act as a map that keeps them from getting lost. Strong transitions also make the talk feel deliberate and well organized rather than a loose collection of points.','Signposting uses transition phrases like ''first'', ''on the other hand'', and ''to sum up'' to mark the boundaries between sections of a talk. Because audiences cannot see your outline, these verbal cues act as a map that keeps them from getting lost. Strong transitions also make the talk feel deliberate and well organized rather than a loose collection of points.',15,'approved','curated-taste');
INSERT INTO "BankQuestion" ("id","skillId","subareaKey","concept","difficulty","type","questionEn","questionPl","optionsEn","optionsPl","correctIndex","acceptedAnswers","orderItems","correctOrder","explanationEn","explanationPl","theoryEn","theoryPl","xp","qualityState","model") VALUES ('bank-speaking-structure-3','speaking','speaking:structure','speaking-structure-3','advanced','mcq','You want your closing line to feel memorable and complete. Which approach best creates that sense of resolution?','You want your closing line to feel memorable and complete. Which approach best creates that sense of resolution?',ARRAY['Call back to the story or image you opened with, tying the ending to the beginning','End abruptly with ''Well, that''s all I have, I guess''','Introduce a brand-new statistic the audience hasn''t heard before','Apologize for running over time and rush off']::text[],ARRAY['Call back to the story or image you opened with, tying the ending to the beginning','End abruptly with ''Well, that''s all I have, I guess''','Introduce a brand-new statistic the audience hasn''t heard before','Apologize for running over time and rush off']::text[],0,ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::int[],'Returning to the opening image or story creates a ''bookend'' that gives the talk a satisfying, deliberate sense of closure.','Returning to the opening image or story creates a ''bookend'' that gives the talk a satisfying, deliberate sense of closure.','The callback or ''bookending'' technique frames a talk by echoing its opening at the close, signaling to the audience that the journey is complete. This narrative symmetry feels intentional and resolves the tension or curiosity raised at the start. Avoid ending with new information or weak filler, which leave listeners feeling the talk simply trailed off.','The callback or ''bookending'' technique frames a talk by echoing its opening at the close, signaling to the audience that the journey is complete. This narrative symmetry feels intentional and resolves the tension or curiosity raised at the start. Avoid ending with new information or weak filler, which leave listeners feeling the talk simply trailed off.',25,'approved','curated-taste');
INSERT INTO "BankQuestion" ("id","skillId","subareaKey","concept","difficulty","type","questionEn","questionPl","optionsEn","optionsPl","correctIndex","acceptedAnswers","orderItems","correctOrder","explanationEn","explanationPl","theoryEn","theoryPl","xp","qualityState","model") VALUES ('bank-speaking-delivery-1','speaking','speaking:delivery','speaking-delivery-1','beginner','truefalse','Pausing briefly after an important point gives the audience time to absorb it and can make the point land harder.','Pausing briefly after an important point gives the audience time to absorb it and can make the point land harder.',ARRAY['True','False']::text[],ARRAY['True','False']::text[],0,ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::int[],'A deliberate pause lets a key idea sink in and adds emphasis, which is why experienced speakers pause rather than rush onward.','A deliberate pause lets a key idea sink in and adds emphasis, which is why experienced speakers pause rather than rush onward.','Pauses are one of the most powerful tools in delivery: they give listeners a moment to process what you just said and they spotlight the words around them. Silence also lets you breathe and reset your pace. New speakers often fear pauses and fill them with ''um'' or rush ahead, but a confident pause reads as poise, not hesitation.','Pauses are one of the most powerful tools in delivery: they give listeners a moment to process what you just said and they spotlight the words around them. Silence also lets you breathe and reset your pace. New speakers often fear pauses and fill them with ''um'' or rush ahead, but a confident pause reads as poise, not hesitation.',10,'approved','curated-taste');
INSERT INTO "BankQuestion" ("id","skillId","subareaKey","concept","difficulty","type","questionEn","questionPl","optionsEn","optionsPl","correctIndex","acceptedAnswers","orderItems","correctOrder","explanationEn","explanationPl","theoryEn","theoryPl","xp","qualityState","model") VALUES ('bank-speaking-delivery-2','speaking','speaking:delivery','speaking-delivery-2','intermediate','mcq','You notice you race through talks and listeners look lost. Which adjustment will most improve how easily people follow you?','You notice you race through talks and listeners look lost. Which adjustment will most improve how easily people follow you?',ARRAY['Slow your overall pace and add short pauses at the end of key sentences','Speak in a flat monotone so every word gets equal weight','Talk even faster to fit more detail into the time','Memorize the script word for word and recite it quickly']::text[],ARRAY['Slow your overall pace and add short pauses at the end of key sentences','Speak in a flat monotone so every word gets equal weight','Talk even faster to fit more detail into the time','Memorize the script word for word and recite it quickly']::text[],0,ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::int[],'Slowing down and pausing at sentence ends gives listeners time to process each idea, which is the core fix for a too-fast delivery.','Slowing down and pausing at sentence ends gives listeners time to process each idea, which is the core fix for a too-fast delivery.','Pacing is how fast you speak and where you pause, and a measured pace dramatically improves comprehension. Nervous speakers tend to accelerate, blurring their words together so the audience can''t keep up. Deliberately slowing down, varying your speed, and pausing at natural breaks gives ideas room to breathe and makes you sound more confident.','Pacing is how fast you speak and where you pause, and a measured pace dramatically improves comprehension. Nervous speakers tend to accelerate, blurring their words together so the audience can''t keep up. Deliberately slowing down, varying your speed, and pausing at natural breaks gives ideas room to breathe and makes you sound more confident.',15,'approved','curated-taste');
INSERT INTO "BankQuestion" ("id","skillId","subareaKey","concept","difficulty","type","questionEn","questionPl","optionsEn","optionsPl","correctIndex","acceptedAnswers","orderItems","correctOrder","explanationEn","explanationPl","theoryEn","theoryPl","xp","qualityState","model") VALUES ('bank-speaking-delivery-3','speaking','speaking:delivery','speaking-delivery-3','advanced','mcq','Throughout a talk your voice stays at one steady pitch and volume. Why does adding vocal variety make you a more effective speaker?','Throughout a talk your voice stays at one steady pitch and volume. Why does adding vocal variety make you a more effective speaker?',ARRAY['Changing pitch, pace, and volume signals emphasis and emotion, keeping the audience engaged and highlighting what matters','It makes the talk longer, which audiences always prefer','A monotone is actually ideal because it sounds calm and authoritative','Volume changes only matter for singers, not speakers']::text[],ARRAY['Changing pitch, pace, and volume signals emphasis and emotion, keeping the audience engaged and highlighting what matters','It makes the talk longer, which audiences always prefer','A monotone is actually ideal because it sounds calm and authoritative','Volume changes only matter for singers, not speakers']::text[],0,ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::int[],'Varying pitch, pace, and volume marks which words carry weight and conveys feeling, preventing the monotony that makes listeners tune out.','Varying pitch, pace, and volume marks which words carry weight and conveys feeling, preventing the monotony that makes listeners tune out.','Vocal variety, the modulation of pitch, pace, and volume, is what keeps a voice engaging and meaningful. A monotone delivery flattens emphasis so the audience can''t tell what is important and quickly loses attention. Strategic changes, like dropping your volume for an intimate point or raising pitch for excitement, guide listeners'' emotions and underline your key ideas.','Vocal variety, the modulation of pitch, pace, and volume, is what keeps a voice engaging and meaningful. A monotone delivery flattens emphasis so the audience can''t tell what is important and quickly loses attention. Strategic changes, like dropping your volume for an intimate point or raising pitch for excitement, guide listeners'' emotions and underline your key ideas.',25,'approved','curated-taste');
INSERT INTO "BankQuestion" ("id","skillId","subareaKey","concept","difficulty","type","questionEn","questionPl","optionsEn","optionsPl","correctIndex","acceptedAnswers","orderItems","correctOrder","explanationEn","explanationPl","theoryEn","theoryPl","xp","qualityState","model") VALUES ('bank-speaking-nerves-1','speaking','speaking:nerves','speaking-nerves-1','beginner','mcq','Just before you walk on stage your heart is pounding and your breathing is shallow. What is a quick, proven way to calm yourself in the moment?','Just before you walk on stage your heart is pounding and your breathing is shallow. What is a quick, proven way to calm yourself in the moment?',ARRAY['Take a few slow, deep breaths, exhaling longer than you inhale','Hold your breath until your turn to speak','Drink several cups of strong coffee to feel energized','Replay every way the talk could go wrong']::text[],ARRAY['Take a few slow, deep breaths, exhaling longer than you inhale','Hold your breath until your turn to speak','Drink several cups of strong coffee to feel energized','Replay every way the talk could go wrong']::text[],0,ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::int[],'Slow, deep breathing with a longer exhale activates the body''s calming response and steadies a racing heart before you begin.','Slow, deep breathing with a longer exhale activates the body''s calming response and steadies a racing heart before you begin.','When we feel anxious, breathing becomes fast and shallow, which fuels the body''s stress response. Deliberate slow breathing, especially a long exhale, triggers the parasympathetic nervous system and physically calms you down. A simple round of deep breaths before speaking lowers your heart rate and steadies your voice.','When we feel anxious, breathing becomes fast and shallow, which fuels the body''s stress response. Deliberate slow breathing, especially a long exhale, triggers the parasympathetic nervous system and physically calms you down. A simple round of deep breaths before speaking lowers your heart rate and steadies your voice.',10,'approved','curated-taste');
INSERT INTO "BankQuestion" ("id","skillId","subareaKey","concept","difficulty","type","questionEn","questionPl","optionsEn","optionsPl","correctIndex","acceptedAnswers","orderItems","correctOrder","explanationEn","explanationPl","theoryEn","theoryPl","xp","qualityState","model") VALUES ('bank-speaking-nerves-2','speaking','speaking:nerves','speaking-nerves-2','intermediate','mcq','A speaker who feels their nerves as ''excitement'' rather than ''fear'' tends to perform better. What is the best explanation for this technique?','A speaker who feels their nerves as ''excitement'' rather than ''fear'' tends to perform better. What is the best explanation for this technique?',ARRAY['Anxiety and excitement feel similar in the body, so relabeling the feeling lets you channel the energy instead of fighting it','It magically removes all physical symptoms of nervousness','Excitement and fear are completely unrelated states','Telling yourself to ''just calm down'' is always more effective']::text[],ARRAY['Anxiety and excitement feel similar in the body, so relabeling the feeling lets you channel the energy instead of fighting it','It magically removes all physical symptoms of nervousness','Excitement and fear are completely unrelated states','Telling yourself to ''just calm down'' is always more effective']::text[],0,ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::int[],'Because the physical arousal of anxiety and excitement is nearly identical, reframing it as excitement is easier than forcing calm and turns the energy to your advantage.','Because the physical arousal of anxiety and excitement is nearly identical, reframing it as excitement is easier than forcing calm and turns the energy to your advantage.','Anxiety reappraisal is the practice of relabeling pre-talk jitters as excitement rather than trying to suppress them. Both states share the same arousal, a racing heart and heightened alertness, so it is easier to shift the label than to switch the body off. Treating the energy as readiness rather than threat helps you channel it into an engaged, lively delivery.','Anxiety reappraisal is the practice of relabeling pre-talk jitters as excitement rather than trying to suppress them. Both states share the same arousal, a racing heart and heightened alertness, so it is easier to shift the label than to switch the body off. Treating the energy as readiness rather than threat helps you channel it into an engaged, lively delivery.',15,'approved','curated-taste');
INSERT INTO "BankQuestion" ("id","skillId","subareaKey","concept","difficulty","type","questionEn","questionPl","optionsEn","optionsPl","correctIndex","acceptedAnswers","orderItems","correctOrder","explanationEn","explanationPl","theoryEn","theoryPl","xp","qualityState","model") VALUES ('bank-speaking-nerves-3','speaking','speaking:nerves','speaking-nerves-3','advanced','mcq','You want a long-term strategy that reliably reduces stage fright over many talks, not just an in-the-moment trick. What works best?','You want a long-term strategy that reliably reduces stage fright over many talks, not just an in-the-moment trick. What works best?',ARRAY['Thorough preparation and repeated rehearsal, ideally out loud and under realistic conditions','Avoiding all practice so the talk feels spontaneous','Picturing the audience in their underwear','Waiting until you no longer feel any nerves before agreeing to speak']::text[],ARRAY['Thorough preparation and repeated rehearsal, ideally out loud and under realistic conditions','Avoiding all practice so the talk feels spontaneous','Picturing the audience in their underwear','Waiting until you no longer feel any nerves before agreeing to speak']::text[],0,ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::int[],'Deep preparation and realistic rehearsal build genuine confidence and automaticity, which is the most dependable way to shrink stage fright over time.','Deep preparation and realistic rehearsal build genuine confidence and automaticity, which is the most dependable way to shrink stage fright over time.','Much speaking anxiety comes from fear of the unknown and of forgetting your material. Rehearsing out loud, ideally standing and simulating real conditions, makes the talk familiar so your brain has fewer surprises to dread. Over repeated exposures this preparation builds lasting confidence, whereas gimmicks offer only momentary relief.','Much speaking anxiety comes from fear of the unknown and of forgetting your material. Rehearsing out loud, ideally standing and simulating real conditions, makes the talk familiar so your brain has fewer surprises to dread. Over repeated exposures this preparation builds lasting confidence, whereas gimmicks offer only momentary relief.',25,'approved','curated-taste');
INSERT INTO "BankQuestion" ("id","skillId","subareaKey","concept","difficulty","type","questionEn","questionPl","optionsEn","optionsPl","correctIndex","acceptedAnswers","orderItems","correctOrder","explanationEn","explanationPl","theoryEn","theoryPl","xp","qualityState","model") VALUES ('bank-speaking-audience-1','speaking','speaking:audience','speaking-audience-1','beginner','mcq','You are preparing the same technical update for a room of engineers versus a room of senior executives. What should most shape how you present it?','You are preparing the same technical update for a room of engineers versus a room of senior executives. What should most shape how you present it?',ARRAY['Tailor the depth, jargon, and focus to what each audience already knows and cares about','Deliver the identical slides and wording to both groups','Use as much specialized jargon as possible to sound credible','Decide the content only by what is easiest for you to prepare']::text[],ARRAY['Tailor the depth, jargon, and focus to what each audience already knows and cares about','Deliver the identical slides and wording to both groups','Use as much specialized jargon as possible to sound credible','Decide the content only by what is easiest for you to prepare']::text[],0,ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::int[],'Adapting your depth, vocabulary, and emphasis to each audience''s knowledge and priorities is the foundation of an effective talk.','Adapting your depth, vocabulary, and emphasis to each audience''s knowledge and priorities is the foundation of an effective talk.','Knowing your audience means understanding their existing knowledge, interests, and what they need from you. The same information should be framed differently for specialists than for decision-makers: experts want detail, while executives want implications and outcomes. Matching your message to the listeners makes it relevant and keeps them engaged.','Knowing your audience means understanding their existing knowledge, interests, and what they need from you. The same information should be framed differently for specialists than for decision-makers: experts want detail, while executives want implications and outcomes. Matching your message to the listeners makes it relevant and keeps them engaged.',10,'approved','curated-taste');
INSERT INTO "BankQuestion" ("id","skillId","subareaKey","concept","difficulty","type","questionEn","questionPl","optionsEn","optionsPl","correctIndex","acceptedAnswers","orderItems","correctOrder","explanationEn","explanationPl","theoryEn","theoryPl","xp","qualityState","model") VALUES ('bank-speaking-audience-2','speaking','speaking:audience','speaking-audience-2','intermediate','mcq','During Q&A someone asks a question and you don''t know the answer. What is the most professional response?','During Q&A someone asks a question and you don''t know the answer. What is the most professional response?',ARRAY['Admit you don''t know, then offer to find out and follow up after the session','Make up a confident-sounding answer on the spot','Dismiss the question as irrelevant and move on','Pretend you didn''t hear it and call on someone else']::text[],ARRAY['Admit you don''t know, then offer to find out and follow up after the session','Make up a confident-sounding answer on the spot','Dismiss the question as irrelevant and move on','Pretend you didn''t hear it and call on someone else']::text[],0,ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::int[],'Honestly acknowledging the gap and promising to follow up protects your credibility, whereas bluffing risks being caught in a wrong answer.','Honestly acknowledging the gap and promising to follow up protects your credibility, whereas bluffing risks being caught in a wrong answer.','Audiences trust speakers who are honest about the limits of their knowledge. Saying ''I don''t know, but I''ll find out and get back to you'' is far more credible than inventing an answer that may be wrong. Offering a genuine follow-up turns a tough question into a chance to build trust rather than lose it.','Audiences trust speakers who are honest about the limits of their knowledge. Saying ''I don''t know, but I''ll find out and get back to you'' is far more credible than inventing an answer that may be wrong. Offering a genuine follow-up turns a tough question into a chance to build trust rather than lose it.',15,'approved','curated-taste');
INSERT INTO "BankQuestion" ("id","skillId","subareaKey","concept","difficulty","type","questionEn","questionPl","optionsEn","optionsPl","correctIndex","acceptedAnswers","orderItems","correctOrder","explanationEn","explanationPl","theoryEn","theoryPl","xp","qualityState","model") VALUES ('bank-speaking-audience-3','speaking','speaking:audience','speaking-audience-3','advanced','mcq','In Q&A a hostile audience member asks a loaded, off-topic question meant to derail you. Which technique lets you stay composed and steer back to your message?','In Q&A a hostile audience member asks a loaded, off-topic question meant to derail you. Which technique lets you stay composed and steer back to your message?',ARRAY['Briefly acknowledge the question, then bridge to a relevant key point with a phrase like ''What''s important here is...''','Argue with the questioner point by point until one of you gives up','Ignore them completely and refuse to respond at all','Abandon your message and let them set the agenda']::text[],ARRAY['Briefly acknowledge the question, then bridge to a relevant key point with a phrase like ''What''s important here is...''','Argue with the questioner point by point until one of you gives up','Ignore them completely and refuse to respond at all','Abandon your message and let them set the agenda']::text[],0,ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::int[],'Bridging acknowledges the question without taking the bait, then transitions to a point you want to make, keeping you in control of the conversation.','Bridging acknowledges the question without taking the bait, then transitions to a point you want to make, keeping you in control of the conversation.','Bridging is a technique borrowed from media training for handling difficult or off-topic questions. You give a brief, respectful acknowledgment, then use a transition phrase to pivot to one of your core messages. This keeps you calm and in control, addresses the moment without getting trapped in a hostile tangent, and returns focus to what you came to say.','Bridging is a technique borrowed from media training for handling difficult or off-topic questions. You give a brief, respectful acknowledgment, then use a transition phrase to pivot to one of your core messages. This keeps you calm and in control, addresses the moment without getting trapped in a hostile tangent, and returns focus to what you came to say.',25,'approved','curated-taste');
INSERT INTO "BankQuestion" ("id","skillId","subareaKey","concept","difficulty","type","questionEn","questionPl","optionsEn","optionsPl","correctIndex","acceptedAnswers","orderItems","correctOrder","explanationEn","explanationPl","theoryEn","theoryPl","xp","qualityState","model") VALUES ('bankq-speaking-structure-b-1','speaking','speaking:structure','speaking-structure-b-1','beginner','mcq','You have ten minutes to give an informative talk. Which overall structure makes it easiest for an audience to follow?','You have ten minutes to give an informative talk. Which overall structure makes it easiest for an audience to follow?',ARRAY['A clear opening that previews the main points, a body that develops them in order, and a closing that summarizes','A long string of facts delivered in whatever order they come to mind','Starting with your conclusion and never explaining how you reached it','Several unrelated anecdotes with no stated purpose']::text[],ARRAY['A clear opening that previews the main points, a body that develops them in order, and a closing that summarizes','A long string of facts delivered in whatever order they come to mind','Starting with your conclusion and never explaining how you reached it','Several unrelated anecdotes with no stated purpose']::text[],0,ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::int[],'A preview-body-summary structure tells the audience where you are going, takes them there, and reminds them where they have been.','A preview-body-summary structure tells the audience where you are going, takes them there, and reminds them where they have been.','Classic speech structure has three parts: tell them what you will say, say it, then tell them what you said. Previewing your points up front gives listeners a mental map. A clear close that restates the key takeaways helps the message stick because people remember beginnings and endings best.','Classic speech structure has three parts: tell them what you will say, say it, then tell them what you said. Previewing your points up front gives listeners a mental map. A clear close that restates the key takeaways helps the message stick because people remember beginnings and endings best.',10,'approved','curated-bank');
INSERT INTO "BankQuestion" ("id","skillId","subareaKey","concept","difficulty","type","questionEn","questionPl","optionsEn","optionsPl","correctIndex","acceptedAnswers","orderItems","correctOrder","explanationEn","explanationPl","theoryEn","theoryPl","xp","qualityState","model") VALUES ('bankq-speaking-structure-b-2','speaking','speaking:structure','speaking-structure-b-2','beginner','truefalse','Signposting phrases such as ''first'', ''next'', and ''finally'' help listeners track where they are in your talk.','Signposting phrases such as ''first'', ''next'', and ''finally'' help listeners track where they are in your talk.',ARRAY['True','False']::text[],ARRAY['True','False']::text[],0,ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::int[],'Signposts act as verbal headings that mark transitions and orient the audience without them needing to take notes.','Signposts act as verbal headings that mark transitions and orient the audience without them needing to take notes.','Listeners cannot rewind a live talk, so they rely on the speaker to flag transitions. Signposting words like first, next, and finally signal movement between points. They reduce the mental effort of following along and make a talk feel organized even when content is dense.','Listeners cannot rewind a live talk, so they rely on the speaker to flag transitions. Signposting words like first, next, and finally signal movement between points. They reduce the mental effort of following along and make a talk feel organized even when content is dense.',10,'approved','curated-bank');
INSERT INTO "BankQuestion" ("id","skillId","subareaKey","concept","difficulty","type","questionEn","questionPl","optionsEn","optionsPl","correctIndex","acceptedAnswers","orderItems","correctOrder","explanationEn","explanationPl","theoryEn","theoryPl","xp","qualityState","model") VALUES ('bankq-speaking-structure-i-1','speaking','speaking:structure','speaking-structure-i-1','intermediate','mcq','You want your three key recommendations to be memorable. Which technique best supports that goal?','You want your three key recommendations to be memorable. Which technique best supports that goal?',ARRAY['Grouping them into a ''rule of three'' with parallel phrasing','Listing nine recommendations so nothing is left out','Burying them in the middle of a long paragraph','Mentioning each one only once, in passing']::text[],ARRAY['Grouping them into a ''rule of three'' with parallel phrasing','Listing nine recommendations so nothing is left out','Burying them in the middle of a long paragraph','Mentioning each one only once, in passing']::text[],0,ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::int[],'The rule of three with parallel phrasing is rhythmically satisfying and easy to recall, so three points land better than a longer list.','The rule of three with parallel phrasing is rhythmically satisfying and easy to recall, so three points land better than a longer list.','Audiences retain a small number of ideas, and sets of three feel complete and rhythmic. Parallel phrasing makes the trio sound deliberate and quotable. Trimming to three forces you to prioritize, which also sharpens the message.','Audiences retain a small number of ideas, and sets of three feel complete and rhythmic. Parallel phrasing makes the trio sound deliberate and quotable. Trimming to three forces you to prioritize, which also sharpens the message.',15,'approved','curated-bank');
INSERT INTO "BankQuestion" ("id","skillId","subareaKey","concept","difficulty","type","questionEn","questionPl","optionsEn","optionsPl","correctIndex","acceptedAnswers","orderItems","correctOrder","explanationEn","explanationPl","theoryEn","theoryPl","xp","qualityState","model") VALUES ('bankq-speaking-structure-i-2','speaking','speaking:structure','speaking-structure-i-2','intermediate','mcq','Your data-heavy talk feels dry. What is the most effective way to make the numbers resonate?','Your data-heavy talk feels dry. What is the most effective way to make the numbers resonate?',ARRAY['Wrap a key statistic inside a short, concrete story about one affected person','Add more decimal places to every figure','Read every row of the spreadsheet aloud','Remove all context and present numbers in isolation']::text[],ARRAY['Wrap a key statistic inside a short, concrete story about one affected person','Add more decimal places to every figure','Read every row of the spreadsheet aloud','Remove all context and present numbers in isolation']::text[],0,ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::int[],'A concrete story gives an abstract statistic emotional weight and a human face, making it memorable.','A concrete story gives an abstract statistic emotional weight and a human face, making it memorable.','People connect with stories more readily than with raw data. Pairing a statistic with a single relatable example translates scale into something felt, not just understood. The narrative provides context that makes the number meaningful rather than forgettable.','People connect with stories more readily than with raw data. Pairing a statistic with a single relatable example translates scale into something felt, not just understood. The narrative provides context that makes the number meaningful rather than forgettable.',15,'approved','curated-bank');
INSERT INTO "BankQuestion" ("id","skillId","subareaKey","concept","difficulty","type","questionEn","questionPl","optionsEn","optionsPl","correctIndex","acceptedAnswers","orderItems","correctOrder","explanationEn","explanationPl","theoryEn","theoryPl","xp","qualityState","model") VALUES ('bankq-speaking-structure-a-1','speaking','speaking:structure','speaking-structure-a-1','advanced','mcq','You are designing a persuasive keynote. Which narrative arc most reliably moves an audience toward action?','You are designing a persuasive keynote. Which narrative arc most reliably moves an audience toward action?',ARRAY['Establish the status quo, introduce a tension or problem, then resolve it with your proposed change and a call to action','Open with administrative housekeeping and end abruptly when time runs out','Present every counterargument first and never state your own position','Repeat a single claim louder each time without development']::text[],ARRAY['Establish the status quo, introduce a tension or problem, then resolve it with your proposed change and a call to action','Open with administrative housekeeping and end abruptly when time runs out','Present every counterargument first and never state your own position','Repeat a single claim louder each time without development']::text[],0,ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::int[],'A status-quo to tension to resolution arc creates a gap the audience wants closed, and your call to action closes it.','A status-quo to tension to resolution arc creates a gap the audience wants closed, and your call to action closes it.','Persuasive talks work like stories: they create a contrast between what is and what could be. The tension between those states generates the desire for change. Ending with a specific, achievable call to action channels that desire into a concrete next step.','Persuasive talks work like stories: they create a contrast between what is and what could be. The tension between those states generates the desire for change. Ending with a specific, achievable call to action channels that desire into a concrete next step.',25,'approved','curated-bank');
INSERT INTO "BankQuestion" ("id","skillId","subareaKey","concept","difficulty","type","questionEn","questionPl","optionsEn","optionsPl","correctIndex","acceptedAnswers","orderItems","correctOrder","explanationEn","explanationPl","theoryEn","theoryPl","xp","qualityState","model") VALUES ('bankq-speaking-structure-a-2','speaking','speaking:structure','speaking-structure-a-2','advanced','truefalse','A ''callback'', where your closing returns to an image or phrase from your opening, can give a talk a satisfying sense of unity.','A ''callback'', where your closing returns to an image or phrase from your opening, can give a talk a satisfying sense of unity.',ARRAY['True','False']::text[],ARRAY['True','False']::text[],0,ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::int[],'Returning to the opening image creates a frame that signals closure and rewards the audience for staying with you.','Returning to the opening image creates a frame that signals closure and rewards the audience for staying with you.','A callback bookends the talk by echoing something the audience already heard, which feels intentional and complete. It reinforces the central theme by revisiting it with the added meaning the talk has supplied. This sense of return is a reliable way to make an ending feel earned rather than abrupt.','A callback bookends the talk by echoing something the audience already heard, which feels intentional and complete. It reinforces the central theme by revisiting it with the added meaning the talk has supplied. This sense of return is a reliable way to make an ending feel earned rather than abrupt.',25,'approved','curated-bank');
INSERT INTO "BankQuestion" ("id","skillId","subareaKey","concept","difficulty","type","questionEn","questionPl","optionsEn","optionsPl","correctIndex","acceptedAnswers","orderItems","correctOrder","explanationEn","explanationPl","theoryEn","theoryPl","xp","qualityState","model") VALUES ('bankq-speaking-delivery-b-1','speaking','speaking:delivery','speaking-delivery-b-1','beginner','mcq','You tend to rush when speaking. What is the simplest delivery fix to help the audience absorb your points?','You tend to rush when speaking. What is the simplest delivery fix to help the audience absorb your points?',ARRAY['Slow your pace and add deliberate pauses after key points','Speak even faster to fit everything in','Drop your volume to a near-whisper throughout','Read directly from a dense script in a monotone']::text[],ARRAY['Slow your pace and add deliberate pauses after key points','Speak even faster to fit everything in','Drop your volume to a near-whisper throughout','Read directly from a dense script in a monotone']::text[],0,ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::int[],'Slowing down and pausing gives listeners time to process and signals which ideas matter.','Slowing down and pausing gives listeners time to process and signals which ideas matter.','Nervous speakers often speed up, which overwhelms listeners. A measured pace plus pauses after important statements lets ideas land and adds emphasis. Silence is not dead air; it gives the audience a moment to absorb what you just said.','Nervous speakers often speed up, which overwhelms listeners. A measured pace plus pauses after important statements lets ideas land and adds emphasis. Silence is not dead air; it gives the audience a moment to absorb what you just said.',10,'approved','curated-bank');
INSERT INTO "BankQuestion" ("id","skillId","subareaKey","concept","difficulty","type","questionEn","questionPl","optionsEn","optionsPl","correctIndex","acceptedAnswers","orderItems","correctOrder","explanationEn","explanationPl","theoryEn","theoryPl","xp","qualityState","model") VALUES ('bankq-speaking-delivery-b-2','speaking','speaking:delivery','speaking-delivery-b-2','beginner','truefalse','Making natural eye contact with individuals across the room helps build connection more than staring at your slides.','Making natural eye contact with individuals across the room helps build connection more than staring at your slides.',ARRAY['True','False']::text[],ARRAY['True','False']::text[],0,ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::int[],'Eye contact signals confidence and engagement and makes listeners feel personally addressed.','Eye contact signals confidence and engagement and makes listeners feel personally addressed.','Eye contact creates a sense of one-to-one connection even in a large room. Looking at your slides or notes the whole time breaks that bond and reads as disengaged. Holding a gaze briefly with different people across the audience helps everyone feel included.','Eye contact creates a sense of one-to-one connection even in a large room. Looking at your slides or notes the whole time breaks that bond and reads as disengaged. Holding a gaze briefly with different people across the audience helps everyone feel included.',10,'approved','curated-bank');
INSERT INTO "BankQuestion" ("id","skillId","subareaKey","concept","difficulty","type","questionEn","questionPl","optionsEn","optionsPl","correctIndex","acceptedAnswers","orderItems","correctOrder","explanationEn","explanationPl","theoryEn","theoryPl","xp","qualityState","model") VALUES ('bankq-speaking-delivery-i-1','speaking','speaking:delivery','speaking-delivery-i-1','intermediate','mcq','Your voice sounds flat and your audience is glazing over. Which vocal adjustment best re-engages them?','Your voice sounds flat and your audience is glazing over. Which vocal adjustment best re-engages them?',ARRAY['Vary your pitch, pace, and volume to match the meaning of what you are saying','Speak in a single steady tone to sound authoritative','Increase your speed uniformly for the rest of the talk','Lower your volume so people lean in for the entire section']::text[],ARRAY['Vary your pitch, pace, and volume to match the meaning of what you are saying','Speak in a single steady tone to sound authoritative','Increase your speed uniformly for the rest of the talk','Lower your volume so people lean in for the entire section']::text[],0,ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::int[],'Vocal variety in pitch, pace, and volume keeps attention and conveys emphasis and emotion.','Vocal variety in pitch, pace, and volume keeps attention and conveys emphasis and emotion.','A monotone delivery flattens meaning and quickly bores listeners. Varying pitch, pace, and volume highlights important ideas and signals shifts in tone. This vocal variety mirrors how we speak naturally in conversation and keeps the audience alert.','A monotone delivery flattens meaning and quickly bores listeners. Varying pitch, pace, and volume highlights important ideas and signals shifts in tone. This vocal variety mirrors how we speak naturally in conversation and keeps the audience alert.',15,'approved','curated-bank');
INSERT INTO "BankQuestion" ("id","skillId","subareaKey","concept","difficulty","type","questionEn","questionPl","optionsEn","optionsPl","correctIndex","acceptedAnswers","orderItems","correctOrder","explanationEn","explanationPl","theoryEn","theoryPl","xp","qualityState","model") VALUES ('bankq-speaking-delivery-i-2','speaking','speaking:delivery','speaking-delivery-i-2','intermediate','mcq','You catch yourself saying ''um'' and ''like'' frequently. What is the most effective way to reduce filler words?','You catch yourself saying ''um'' and ''like'' frequently. What is the most effective way to reduce filler words?',ARRAY['Pause silently where you would have said a filler','Speak faster so the fillers slip by unnoticed','Add even more fillers so they sound intentional','Memorize the talk word for word and recite it rigidly']::text[],ARRAY['Pause silently where you would have said a filler','Speak faster so the fillers slip by unnoticed','Add even more fillers so they sound intentional','Memorize the talk word for word and recite it rigidly']::text[],0,ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::int[],'Fillers usually fill thinking time, so a deliberate silent pause replaces them while sounding more composed.','Fillers usually fill thinking time, so a deliberate silent pause replaces them while sounding more composed.','Filler words tend to appear when the brain needs a moment to find the next thought. Replacing that moment with a brief silence removes the filler and reads as confident and considered. Becoming comfortable with short pauses is the core skill behind clean delivery.','Filler words tend to appear when the brain needs a moment to find the next thought. Replacing that moment with a brief silence removes the filler and reads as confident and considered. Becoming comfortable with short pauses is the core skill behind clean delivery.',15,'approved','curated-bank');
INSERT INTO "BankQuestion" ("id","skillId","subareaKey","concept","difficulty","type","questionEn","questionPl","optionsEn","optionsPl","correctIndex","acceptedAnswers","orderItems","correctOrder","explanationEn","explanationPl","theoryEn","theoryPl","xp","qualityState","model") VALUES ('bankq-speaking-delivery-a-1','speaking','speaking:delivery','speaking-delivery-a-1','advanced','mcq','You want gestures to strengthen rather than distract from your message. Which approach is best?','You want gestures to strengthen rather than distract from your message. Which approach is best?',ARRAY['Use purposeful gestures that illustrate specific ideas and keep hands at rest otherwise','Keep both hands rigidly at your sides the entire time','Make constant, repetitive hand movements regardless of content','Grip the lectern tightly so your hands never move']::text[],ARRAY['Use purposeful gestures that illustrate specific ideas and keep hands at rest otherwise','Keep both hands rigidly at your sides the entire time','Make constant, repetitive hand movements regardless of content','Grip the lectern tightly so your hands never move']::text[],0,ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::int[],'Gestures that map to specific ideas reinforce meaning, while a neutral resting position prevents nervous fidgeting from distracting.','Gestures that map to specific ideas reinforce meaning, while a neutral resting position prevents nervous fidgeting from distracting.','Effective gestures are deliberate and tied to what you are saying, such as showing size, sequence, or contrast. Constant or random movement becomes visual noise that competes with your words. A calm resting position between gestures lets each intentional movement carry weight.','Effective gestures are deliberate and tied to what you are saying, such as showing size, sequence, or contrast. Constant or random movement becomes visual noise that competes with your words. A calm resting position between gestures lets each intentional movement carry weight.',25,'approved','curated-bank');
INSERT INTO "BankQuestion" ("id","skillId","subareaKey","concept","difficulty","type","questionEn","questionPl","optionsEn","optionsPl","correctIndex","acceptedAnswers","orderItems","correctOrder","explanationEn","explanationPl","theoryEn","theoryPl","xp","qualityState","model") VALUES ('bankq-speaking-delivery-a-2','speaking','speaking:delivery','speaking-delivery-a-2','advanced','truefalse','Strategic silence immediately before a key statement can heighten its impact more than rushing into it.','Strategic silence immediately before a key statement can heighten its impact more than rushing into it.',ARRAY['True','False']::text[],ARRAY['True','False']::text[],0,ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::int[],'A pause before a key line creates anticipation and focuses attention on what follows.','A pause before a key line creates anticipation and focuses attention on what follows.','Silence is a powerful delivery tool, not a gap to fill. A deliberate pause before an important point builds tension and signals that something worth hearing is coming. Skilled speakers use these pauses to frame their most important lines and let them resonate.','Silence is a powerful delivery tool, not a gap to fill. A deliberate pause before an important point builds tension and signals that something worth hearing is coming. Skilled speakers use these pauses to frame their most important lines and let them resonate.',25,'approved','curated-bank');
INSERT INTO "BankQuestion" ("id","skillId","subareaKey","concept","difficulty","type","questionEn","questionPl","optionsEn","optionsPl","correctIndex","acceptedAnswers","orderItems","correctOrder","explanationEn","explanationPl","theoryEn","theoryPl","xp","qualityState","model") VALUES ('bankq-speaking-nerves-b-1','speaking','speaking:nerves','speaking-nerves-b-1','beginner','mcq','Minutes before going on stage your heart is racing. Which technique most directly calms your nervous system?','Minutes before going on stage your heart is racing. Which technique most directly calms your nervous system?',ARRAY['Slow, deep diaphragmatic breathing','Holding your breath until you feel calmer','Drinking several cups of coffee for energy','Replaying every possible thing that could go wrong']::text[],ARRAY['Slow, deep diaphragmatic breathing','Holding your breath until you feel calmer','Drinking several cups of coffee for energy','Replaying every possible thing that could go wrong']::text[],0,ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::int[],'Slow diaphragmatic breathing lowers heart rate and signals the body to relax before you speak.','Slow diaphragmatic breathing lowers heart rate and signals the body to relax before you speak.','Pre-talk nerves trigger a fight-or-flight response that speeds the heart and shortens the breath. Slow, deep breathing from the diaphragm activates the body''s calming response and steadies the voice. A few measured breaths before you begin can noticeably reduce the physical symptoms of anxiety.','Pre-talk nerves trigger a fight-or-flight response that speeds the heart and shortens the breath. Slow, deep breathing from the diaphragm activates the body''s calming response and steadies the voice. A few measured breaths before you begin can noticeably reduce the physical symptoms of anxiety.',10,'approved','curated-bank');
INSERT INTO "BankQuestion" ("id","skillId","subareaKey","concept","difficulty","type","questionEn","questionPl","optionsEn","optionsPl","correctIndex","acceptedAnswers","orderItems","correctOrder","explanationEn","explanationPl","theoryEn","theoryPl","xp","qualityState","model") VALUES ('bankq-speaking-nerves-b-2','speaking','speaking:nerves','speaking-nerves-b-2','beginner','truefalse','Thorough preparation and rehearsal generally reduce performance anxiety.','Thorough preparation and rehearsal generally reduce performance anxiety.',ARRAY['True','False']::text[],ARRAY['True','False']::text[],0,ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::int[],'Knowing your material well removes uncertainty, which is a major source of nervousness.','Knowing your material well removes uncertainty, which is a major source of nervousness.','Much speaking anxiety comes from fear of forgetting or fumbling. Rehearsing out loud builds familiarity so the talk feels automatic under pressure. The better you know your opening and your transitions, the less there is to worry about on the day.','Much speaking anxiety comes from fear of forgetting or fumbling. Rehearsing out loud builds familiarity so the talk feels automatic under pressure. The better you know your opening and your transitions, the less there is to worry about on the day.',10,'approved','curated-bank');
INSERT INTO "BankQuestion" ("id","skillId","subareaKey","concept","difficulty","type","questionEn","questionPl","optionsEn","optionsPl","correctIndex","acceptedAnswers","orderItems","correctOrder","explanationEn","explanationPl","theoryEn","theoryPl","xp","qualityState","model") VALUES ('bankq-speaking-nerves-i-1','speaking','speaking:nerves','speaking-nerves-i-1','intermediate','mcq','You feel a surge of adrenaline before speaking. Which mindset reframe is most useful?','You feel a surge of adrenaline before speaking. Which mindset reframe is most useful?',ARRAY['Interpret the arousal as excitement and energy that will help your performance','Tell yourself the feeling means you are about to fail','Try to suppress all emotion and feel nothing','Assume the audience can see exactly how scared you are']::text[],ARRAY['Interpret the arousal as excitement and energy that will help your performance','Tell yourself the feeling means you are about to fail','Try to suppress all emotion and feel nothing','Assume the audience can see exactly how scared you are']::text[],0,ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::int[],'Reframing arousal as excitement keeps the energy without the dread, and it is easier than forcing yourself to feel calm.','Reframing arousal as excitement keeps the energy without the dread, and it is easier than forcing yourself to feel calm.','Anxiety and excitement produce nearly identical bodily signals, so the body is already primed; the label you give it shapes the experience. Telling yourself ''I am excited'' channels that energy into engaged delivery. This reframe is more achievable than trying to extinguish the adrenaline entirely.','Anxiety and excitement produce nearly identical bodily signals, so the body is already primed; the label you give it shapes the experience. Telling yourself ''I am excited'' channels that energy into engaged delivery. This reframe is more achievable than trying to extinguish the adrenaline entirely.',15,'approved','curated-bank');
INSERT INTO "BankQuestion" ("id","skillId","subareaKey","concept","difficulty","type","questionEn","questionPl","optionsEn","optionsPl","correctIndex","acceptedAnswers","orderItems","correctOrder","explanationEn","explanationPl","theoryEn","theoryPl","xp","qualityState","model") VALUES ('bankq-speaking-nerves-i-2','speaking','speaking:nerves','speaking-nerves-i-2','intermediate','mcq','You lose your place mid-talk and your mind goes blank. What is the best in-the-moment recovery?','You lose your place mid-talk and your mind goes blank. What is the best in-the-moment recovery?',ARRAY['Pause, take a breath, glance at your notes or last slide, and resume','Apologize repeatedly and announce that you have frozen','Speed up and improvise unrelated content to fill the silence','Walk off and end the talk early']::text[],ARRAY['Pause, take a breath, glance at your notes or last slide, and resume','Apologize repeatedly and announce that you have frozen','Speed up and improvise unrelated content to fill the silence','Walk off and end the talk early']::text[],0,ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::int[],'A calm pause and a quick glance at your notes lets you find your place without drawing attention to the lapse.','A calm pause and a quick glance at your notes lets you find your place without drawing attention to the lapse.','Brief silences feel much longer to the speaker than to the audience, so a short pause goes mostly unnoticed. Taking a breath and checking your notes or current slide reorients you quickly. Drawing attention to the slip with apologies usually makes it more memorable than the slip itself.','Brief silences feel much longer to the speaker than to the audience, so a short pause goes mostly unnoticed. Taking a breath and checking your notes or current slide reorients you quickly. Drawing attention to the slip with apologies usually makes it more memorable than the slip itself.',15,'approved','curated-bank');
INSERT INTO "BankQuestion" ("id","skillId","subareaKey","concept","difficulty","type","questionEn","questionPl","optionsEn","optionsPl","correctIndex","acceptedAnswers","orderItems","correctOrder","explanationEn","explanationPl","theoryEn","theoryPl","xp","qualityState","model") VALUES ('bankq-speaking-nerves-a-1','speaking','speaking:nerves','speaking-nerves-a-1','advanced','mcq','You want a long-term strategy to build genuine confidence rather than just managing symptoms on the day. Which is most effective?','You want a long-term strategy to build genuine confidence rather than just managing symptoms on the day. Which is most effective?',ARRAY['Seek frequent low-stakes speaking opportunities to build experience through gradual exposure','Avoid all speaking until you feel completely fearless','Rely on a single high-pressure event to overcome the fear at once','Read books about speaking but never actually speak']::text[],ARRAY['Seek frequent low-stakes speaking opportunities to build experience through gradual exposure','Avoid all speaking until you feel completely fearless','Rely on a single high-pressure event to overcome the fear at once','Read books about speaking but never actually speak']::text[],0,ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::int[],'Gradual, repeated exposure desensitizes the fear and builds real competence and confidence over time.','Gradual, repeated exposure desensitizes the fear and builds real competence and confidence over time.','Confidence is built through repeated successful experience, not avoidance. Seeking frequent low-stakes chances to speak lets you accumulate evidence that you can handle it. This gradual exposure steadily lowers anxiety while sharpening skill, which a single dramatic attempt cannot reliably do.','Confidence is built through repeated successful experience, not avoidance. Seeking frequent low-stakes chances to speak lets you accumulate evidence that you can handle it. This gradual exposure steadily lowers anxiety while sharpening skill, which a single dramatic attempt cannot reliably do.',25,'approved','curated-bank');
INSERT INTO "BankQuestion" ("id","skillId","subareaKey","concept","difficulty","type","questionEn","questionPl","optionsEn","optionsPl","correctIndex","acceptedAnswers","orderItems","correctOrder","explanationEn","explanationPl","theoryEn","theoryPl","xp","qualityState","model") VALUES ('bankq-speaking-nerves-a-2','speaking','speaking:nerves','speaking-nerves-a-2','advanced','truefalse','Visualizing yourself delivering the talk successfully can reduce anxiety and improve actual performance.','Visualizing yourself delivering the talk successfully can reduce anxiety and improve actual performance.',ARRAY['True','False']::text[],ARRAY['True','False']::text[],0,ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::int[],'Mental rehearsal primes confidence and familiarity, much like physical rehearsal does.','Mental rehearsal primes confidence and familiarity, much like physical rehearsal does.','Visualization is a technique used by athletes and performers to prepare for high-pressure moments. Vividly imagining a smooth, successful delivery builds a sense of familiarity and lowers anticipatory anxiety. It complements physical rehearsal by training the mind to expect success rather than disaster.','Visualization is a technique used by athletes and performers to prepare for high-pressure moments. Vividly imagining a smooth, successful delivery builds a sense of familiarity and lowers anticipatory anxiety. It complements physical rehearsal by training the mind to expect success rather than disaster.',25,'approved','curated-bank');
INSERT INTO "BankQuestion" ("id","skillId","subareaKey","concept","difficulty","type","questionEn","questionPl","optionsEn","optionsPl","correctIndex","acceptedAnswers","orderItems","correctOrder","explanationEn","explanationPl","theoryEn","theoryPl","xp","qualityState","model") VALUES ('bankq-speaking-audience-b-1','speaking','speaking:audience','speaking-audience-b-1','beginner','mcq','You are preparing a talk for a non-technical audience on a technical subject. What should guide your choices most?','You are preparing a talk for a non-technical audience on a technical subject. What should guide your choices most?',ARRAY['Tailoring vocabulary, examples, and depth to what this audience already knows and cares about','Using as much specialist jargon as possible to sound credible','Delivering the exact same talk you would give to experts','Ignoring the audience and focusing only on covering all the content']::text[],ARRAY['Tailoring vocabulary, examples, and depth to what this audience already knows and cares about','Using as much specialist jargon as possible to sound credible','Delivering the exact same talk you would give to experts','Ignoring the audience and focusing only on covering all the content']::text[],0,ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::int[],'Adapting language and examples to the audience''s knowledge ensures they actually understand and stay engaged.','Adapting language and examples to the audience''s knowledge ensures they actually understand and stay engaged.','Audience awareness means starting from what listeners know and value rather than from everything you know. Choosing accessible language and relevant examples bridges the gap to a non-expert audience. A talk that ignores who is listening will lose people no matter how accurate it is.','Audience awareness means starting from what listeners know and value rather than from everything you know. Choosing accessible language and relevant examples bridges the gap to a non-expert audience. A talk that ignores who is listening will lose people no matter how accurate it is.',10,'approved','curated-bank');
INSERT INTO "BankQuestion" ("id","skillId","subareaKey","concept","difficulty","type","questionEn","questionPl","optionsEn","optionsPl","correctIndex","acceptedAnswers","orderItems","correctOrder","explanationEn","explanationPl","theoryEn","theoryPl","xp","qualityState","model") VALUES ('bankq-speaking-audience-b-2','speaking','speaking:audience','speaking-audience-b-2','beginner','truefalse','If you do not know the answer to an audience question, it is better to admit it and offer to follow up than to bluff.','If you do not know the answer to an audience question, it is better to admit it and offer to follow up than to bluff.',ARRAY['True','False']::text[],ARRAY['True','False']::text[],0,ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::int[],'Honesty preserves credibility, while a bluff risks being exposed and undermining trust.','Honesty preserves credibility, while a bluff risks being exposed and undermining trust.','Audiences respect speakers who acknowledge the limits of their knowledge. Saying you will find out and follow up is credible and professional. Bluffing an answer risks being wrong in front of everyone, which damages trust far more than a candid ''I don''t know''.','Audiences respect speakers who acknowledge the limits of their knowledge. Saying you will find out and follow up is credible and professional. Bluffing an answer risks being wrong in front of everyone, which damages trust far more than a candid ''I don''t know''.',10,'approved','curated-bank');
INSERT INTO "BankQuestion" ("id","skillId","subareaKey","concept","difficulty","type","questionEn","questionPl","optionsEn","optionsPl","correctIndex","acceptedAnswers","orderItems","correctOrder","explanationEn","explanationPl","theoryEn","theoryPl","xp","qualityState","model") VALUES ('bankq-speaking-audience-i-1','speaking','speaking:audience','speaking-audience-i-1','intermediate','mcq','During Q&A you get a rambling, multi-part question. What is the best way to handle it?','During Q&A you get a rambling, multi-part question. What is the best way to handle it?',ARRAY['Briefly restate the core question you will answer, then respond to that','Try to answer every tangent in the exact order given','Ignore the question entirely and move on','Interrupt the questioner before they finish']::text[],ARRAY['Briefly restate the core question you will answer, then respond to that','Try to answer every tangent in the exact order given','Ignore the question entirely and move on','Interrupt the questioner before they finish']::text[],0,ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::int[],'Restating the core question focuses the exchange, confirms understanding, and lets the whole room follow your answer.','Restating the core question focuses the exchange, confirms understanding, and lets the whole room follow your answer.','Long questions often contain one main point buried in detail. Paraphrasing it back confirms you understood and makes the question audible to everyone. It also lets you frame a focused answer instead of getting lost in every tangent.','Long questions often contain one main point buried in detail. Paraphrasing it back confirms you understood and makes the question audible to everyone. It also lets you frame a focused answer instead of getting lost in every tangent.',15,'approved','curated-bank');
INSERT INTO "BankQuestion" ("id","skillId","subareaKey","concept","difficulty","type","questionEn","questionPl","optionsEn","optionsPl","correctIndex","acceptedAnswers","orderItems","correctOrder","explanationEn","explanationPl","theoryEn","theoryPl","xp","qualityState","model") VALUES ('bankq-speaking-audience-i-2','speaking','speaking:audience','speaking-audience-i-2','intermediate','mcq','A questioner pushes you off-topic toward an issue you would rather not dwell on. Which technique keeps control respectfully?','A questioner pushes you off-topic toward an issue you would rather not dwell on. Which technique keeps control respectfully?',ARRAY['Bridge: briefly acknowledge the point, then steer back to your key message','Argue with the questioner until they concede','Pretend you did not hear and stay silent','Abandon your message and follow wherever the question leads']::text[],ARRAY['Bridge: briefly acknowledge the point, then steer back to your key message','Argue with the questioner until they concede','Pretend you did not hear and stay silent','Abandon your message and follow wherever the question leads']::text[],0,ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::int[],'Bridging acknowledges the question while transitioning back to the message you came to deliver.','Bridging acknowledges the question while transitioning back to the message you came to deliver.','Bridging is a technique for acknowledging a question and then linking back to your main points. A short phrase like ''that''s worth noting, and what really matters here is...'' redirects without dismissing the questioner. It keeps you on message while still treating the audience with respect.','Bridging is a technique for acknowledging a question and then linking back to your main points. A short phrase like ''that''s worth noting, and what really matters here is...'' redirects without dismissing the questioner. It keeps you on message while still treating the audience with respect.',15,'approved','curated-bank');
INSERT INTO "BankQuestion" ("id","skillId","subareaKey","concept","difficulty","type","questionEn","questionPl","optionsEn","optionsPl","correctIndex","acceptedAnswers","orderItems","correctOrder","explanationEn","explanationPl","theoryEn","theoryPl","xp","qualityState","model") VALUES ('bankq-speaking-audience-a-1','speaking','speaking:audience','speaking-audience-a-1','advanced','mcq','A hostile audience member challenges your credibility aggressively during Q&A. What is the most effective response?','A hostile audience member challenges your credibility aggressively during Q&A. What is the most effective response?',ARRAY['Stay calm, acknowledge the concern, respond to the substance, and avoid mirroring the hostility','Match their aggression to show you will not be intimidated','Dismiss them and refuse to engage at all','Become defensive and over-explain at length']::text[],ARRAY['Stay calm, acknowledge the concern, respond to the substance, and avoid mirroring the hostility','Match their aggression to show you will not be intimidated','Dismiss them and refuse to engage at all','Become defensive and over-explain at length']::text[],0,ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::int[],'A calm, substantive response defuses hostility and preserves your authority in front of the rest of the room.','A calm, substantive response defuses hostility and preserves your authority in front of the rest of the room.','Hostile questions are partly performances for the audience, so your composure matters as much as your content. Staying calm and engaging the substance signals confidence and fairness. Mirroring the aggression escalates the conflict and can turn the rest of the room against you.','Hostile questions are partly performances for the audience, so your composure matters as much as your content. Staying calm and engaging the substance signals confidence and fairness. Mirroring the aggression escalates the conflict and can turn the rest of the room against you.',25,'approved','curated-bank');
INSERT INTO "BankQuestion" ("id","skillId","subareaKey","concept","difficulty","type","questionEn","questionPl","optionsEn","optionsPl","correctIndex","acceptedAnswers","orderItems","correctOrder","explanationEn","explanationPl","theoryEn","theoryPl","xp","qualityState","model") VALUES ('bankq-speaking-audience-a-2','speaking','speaking:audience','speaking-audience-a-2','advanced','truefalse','Reading the room and adjusting your pace or content when the audience looks confused or disengaged is a hallmark of a skilled speaker.','Reading the room and adjusting your pace or content when the audience looks confused or disengaged is a hallmark of a skilled speaker.',ARRAY['True','False']::text[],ARRAY['True','False']::text[],0,ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::int[],'Responsive speakers monitor audience cues and adapt in real time to keep the room with them.','Responsive speakers monitor audience cues and adapt in real time to keep the room with them.','Audience feedback is constant and nonverbal: puzzled faces, lost attention, or nods of agreement. Skilled speakers watch for these cues and adjust by slowing down, adding an example, or moving on. This responsiveness keeps the talk a two-way connection rather than a rigid recitation.','Audience feedback is constant and nonverbal: puzzled faces, lost attention, or nods of agreement. Skilled speakers watch for these cues and adjust by slowing down, adding an example, or moving on. This responsiveness keeps the talk a two-way connection rather than a rigid recitation.',25,'approved','curated-bank');
INSERT INTO "BankQuestion" ("id","skillId","subareaKey","concept","difficulty","type","questionEn","questionPl","optionsEn","optionsPl","correctIndex","acceptedAnswers","orderItems","correctOrder","explanationEn","explanationPl","theoryEn","theoryPl","xp","qualityState","model") VALUES ('bank-ai-ml-1','ai','ai:ml','ai-ml-1','beginner','mcq','A model is trained on emails that are each already labeled as ''spam'' or ''not spam'' so it can label new emails. What type of machine learning is this?','A model is trained on emails that are each already labeled as ''spam'' or ''not spam'' so it can label new emails. What type of machine learning is this?',ARRAY['Supervised learning','Unsupervised learning','Reinforcement learning','Clustering']::text[],ARRAY['Supervised learning','Unsupervised learning','Reinforcement learning','Clustering']::text[],0,ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::int[],'Learning from input examples paired with known correct labels is the defining characteristic of supervised learning.','Learning from input examples paired with known correct labels is the defining characteristic of supervised learning.','Supervised learning trains a model on data where each example has a known target answer, so the model learns to map inputs to those labels. Once trained, it predicts labels for new, unseen inputs. Common tasks include classification (predicting categories) and regression (predicting numbers).','Supervised learning trains a model on data where each example has a known target answer, so the model learns to map inputs to those labels. Once trained, it predicts labels for new, unseen inputs. Common tasks include classification (predicting categories) and regression (predicting numbers).',10,'approved','curated-taste');
INSERT INTO "BankQuestion" ("id","skillId","subareaKey","concept","difficulty","type","questionEn","questionPl","optionsEn","optionsPl","correctIndex","acceptedAnswers","orderItems","correctOrder","explanationEn","explanationPl","theoryEn","theoryPl","xp","qualityState","model") VALUES ('bank-ai-ml-2','ai','ai:ml','ai-ml-2','intermediate','mcq','You have a dataset of customer purchases with no labels, and you want to discover natural groupings of similar customers. Which approach fits best?','You have a dataset of customer purchases with no labels, and you want to discover natural groupings of similar customers. Which approach fits best?',ARRAY['Clustering, an unsupervised method','Linear regression, a supervised method','Logistic regression, a supervised method','A labeled train-test split']::text[],ARRAY['Clustering, an unsupervised method','Linear regression, a supervised method','Logistic regression, a supervised method','A labeled train-test split']::text[],0,ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::int[],'Finding groupings in unlabeled data without predefined categories is unsupervised learning, and clustering is its canonical technique.','Finding groupings in unlabeled data without predefined categories is unsupervised learning, and clustering is its canonical technique.','Unsupervised learning works with data that has no target labels, aiming to uncover hidden structure. Clustering groups similar examples together, while other unsupervised methods reduce dimensionality or detect anomalies. Because there are no ground-truth answers, results are evaluated by how meaningful or useful the discovered structure is.','Unsupervised learning works with data that has no target labels, aiming to uncover hidden structure. Clustering groups similar examples together, while other unsupervised methods reduce dimensionality or detect anomalies. Because there are no ground-truth answers, results are evaluated by how meaningful or useful the discovered structure is.',15,'approved','curated-taste');
INSERT INTO "BankQuestion" ("id","skillId","subareaKey","concept","difficulty","type","questionEn","questionPl","optionsEn","optionsPl","correctIndex","acceptedAnswers","orderItems","correctOrder","explanationEn","explanationPl","theoryEn","theoryPl","xp","qualityState","model") VALUES ('bank-ai-ml-3','ai','ai:ml','ai-ml-3','advanced','mcq','A model reaches 99% accuracy on its training data but only 70% on a held-out test set. What is the most likely problem and a reasonable fix?','A model reaches 99% accuracy on its training data but only 70% on a held-out test set. What is the most likely problem and a reasonable fix?',ARRAY['Overfitting; add regularization or more training data','Underfitting; make the model much larger','The test set is too easy; remove it','Data leakage; raise the learning rate']::text[],ARRAY['Overfitting; add regularization or more training data','Underfitting; make the model much larger','The test set is too easy; remove it','Data leakage; raise the learning rate']::text[],0,ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::int[],'A large gap between high training accuracy and lower test accuracy signals overfitting, which regularization or more diverse data helps reduce.','A large gap between high training accuracy and lower test accuracy signals overfitting, which regularization or more diverse data helps reduce.','Overfitting happens when a model memorizes quirks and noise in the training data instead of learning patterns that generalize. The telltale sign is strong training performance paired with weak performance on new data. Remedies include regularization, gathering more or more varied data, simplifying the model, and early stopping during training.','Overfitting happens when a model memorizes quirks and noise in the training data instead of learning patterns that generalize. The telltale sign is strong training performance paired with weak performance on new data. Remedies include regularization, gathering more or more varied data, simplifying the model, and early stopping during training.',25,'approved','curated-taste');
INSERT INTO "BankQuestion" ("id","skillId","subareaKey","concept","difficulty","type","questionEn","questionPl","optionsEn","optionsPl","correctIndex","acceptedAnswers","orderItems","correctOrder","explanationEn","explanationPl","theoryEn","theoryPl","xp","qualityState","model") VALUES ('bank-ai-neural-1','ai','ai:neural','ai-neural-1','beginner','truefalse','Without a non-linear activation function, a stack of neural network layers can only represent linear relationships between inputs and outputs.','Without a non-linear activation function, a stack of neural network layers can only represent linear relationships between inputs and outputs.',ARRAY['True','False']::text[],ARRAY['True','False']::text[],0,ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::int[],'Composing purely linear layers still yields a single linear function, so non-linear activations are what let networks model complex patterns.','Composing purely linear layers still yields a single linear function, so non-linear activations are what let networks model complex patterns.','Each layer of a neural network typically computes a weighted sum followed by an activation function. If the activation were linear (or absent), stacking layers would collapse into one equivalent linear transformation, limiting the network to straight-line relationships. Non-linear activations like ReLU, sigmoid, or tanh break this collapse, enabling networks to approximate complex, curved decision boundaries.','Each layer of a neural network typically computes a weighted sum followed by an activation function. If the activation were linear (or absent), stacking layers would collapse into one equivalent linear transformation, limiting the network to straight-line relationships. Non-linear activations like ReLU, sigmoid, or tanh break this collapse, enabling networks to approximate complex, curved decision boundaries.',10,'approved','curated-taste');
INSERT INTO "BankQuestion" ("id","skillId","subareaKey","concept","difficulty","type","questionEn","questionPl","optionsEn","optionsPl","correctIndex","acceptedAnswers","orderItems","correctOrder","explanationEn","explanationPl","theoryEn","theoryPl","xp","qualityState","model") VALUES ('bank-ai-neural-2','ai','ai:neural','ai-neural-2','intermediate','mcq','In gradient descent, what role does the gradient of the loss function play during a training step?','In gradient descent, what role does the gradient of the loss function play during a training step?',ARRAY['It points in the direction of steepest increase, so we step opposite to it to reduce loss','It directly sets the final weight values in one step','It measures how accurate the model is on the test set','It randomly shuffles the training data between epochs']::text[],ARRAY['It points in the direction of steepest increase, so we step opposite to it to reduce loss','It directly sets the final weight values in one step','It measures how accurate the model is on the test set','It randomly shuffles the training data between epochs']::text[],0,ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::int[],'The gradient indicates the direction of steepest loss increase, so updating weights in the opposite direction lowers the loss.','The gradient indicates the direction of steepest loss increase, so updating weights in the opposite direction lowers the loss.','Gradient descent improves a model by repeatedly nudging its weights to reduce a loss that measures error. The gradient is the vector of partial derivatives showing how the loss changes with each weight; it points uphill, so we move against it. The learning rate controls how big each step is, balancing speed against the risk of overshooting.','Gradient descent improves a model by repeatedly nudging its weights to reduce a loss that measures error. The gradient is the vector of partial derivatives showing how the loss changes with each weight; it points uphill, so we move against it. The learning rate controls how big each step is, balancing speed against the risk of overshooting.',15,'approved','curated-taste');
INSERT INTO "BankQuestion" ("id","skillId","subareaKey","concept","difficulty","type","questionEn","questionPl","optionsEn","optionsPl","correctIndex","acceptedAnswers","orderItems","correctOrder","explanationEn","explanationPl","theoryEn","theoryPl","xp","qualityState","model") VALUES ('bank-ai-neural-3','ai','ai:neural','ai-neural-3','advanced','mcq','What is the core purpose of the backpropagation algorithm in training a neural network?','What is the core purpose of the backpropagation algorithm in training a neural network?',ARRAY['To efficiently compute the gradient of the loss with respect to every weight using the chain rule','To choose the best activation function for each layer automatically','To split the dataset into training and test sets','To increase the learning rate when training slows down']::text[],ARRAY['To efficiently compute the gradient of the loss with respect to every weight using the chain rule','To choose the best activation function for each layer automatically','To split the dataset into training and test sets','To increase the learning rate when training slows down']::text[],0,ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::int[],'Backpropagation applies the chain rule backward through the network to compute each weight''s gradient efficiently so gradient descent can update them.','Backpropagation applies the chain rule backward through the network to compute each weight''s gradient efficiently so gradient descent can update them.','Backpropagation calculates how much each weight contributed to the network''s error by propagating the loss backward layer by layer. It reuses intermediate results via the chain rule of calculus, making gradient computation efficient even for millions of parameters. These gradients are then fed to an optimizer such as gradient descent, which adjusts the weights to reduce the loss.','Backpropagation calculates how much each weight contributed to the network''s error by propagating the loss backward layer by layer. It reuses intermediate results via the chain rule of calculus, making gradient computation efficient even for millions of parameters. These gradients are then fed to an optimizer such as gradient descent, which adjusts the weights to reduce the loss.',25,'approved','curated-taste');
INSERT INTO "BankQuestion" ("id","skillId","subareaKey","concept","difficulty","type","questionEn","questionPl","optionsEn","optionsPl","correctIndex","acceptedAnswers","orderItems","correctOrder","explanationEn","explanationPl","theoryEn","theoryPl","xp","qualityState","model") VALUES ('bank-ai-llms-1','ai','ai:llms','ai-llms-1','beginner','mcq','When a large language model processes text, what is a ''token''?','When a large language model processes text, what is a ''token''?',ARRAY['A chunk of text such as a word or word-piece that the model reads and predicts','A security key that authorizes the API request','A single pixel in an input image','The model''s final confidence score for an answer']::text[],ARRAY['A chunk of text such as a word or word-piece that the model reads and predicts','A security key that authorizes the API request','A single pixel in an input image','The model''s final confidence score for an answer']::text[],0,ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::int[],'Language models break text into tokens (words or sub-word pieces) as the basic units they read and generate.','Language models break text into tokens (words or sub-word pieces) as the basic units they read and generate.','Tokens are the small pieces of text, often whole words or fragments of words, that a language model operates on. Text is split into tokens before processing, and the model generates output one token at a time. Token counts matter in practice because they determine how much text fits in a request and often how usage is priced.','Tokens are the small pieces of text, often whole words or fragments of words, that a language model operates on. Text is split into tokens before processing, and the model generates output one token at a time. Token counts matter in practice because they determine how much text fits in a request and often how usage is priced.',10,'approved','curated-taste');
INSERT INTO "BankQuestion" ("id","skillId","subareaKey","concept","difficulty","type","questionEn","questionPl","optionsEn","optionsPl","correctIndex","acceptedAnswers","orderItems","correctOrder","explanationEn","explanationPl","theoryEn","theoryPl","xp","qualityState","model") VALUES ('bank-ai-llms-2','ai','ai:llms','ai-llms-2','intermediate','mcq','Two words that are used in similar contexts, like ''cat'' and ''kitten'', tend to have embeddings that are close together in vector space. What does this illustrate?','Two words that are used in similar contexts, like ''cat'' and ''kitten'', tend to have embeddings that are close together in vector space. What does this illustrate?',ARRAY['Embeddings capture semantic similarity as geometric closeness','Embeddings store the exact spelling of each word','Embeddings are random and carry no meaning','Embeddings only work for numbers, not words']::text[],ARRAY['Embeddings capture semantic similarity as geometric closeness','Embeddings store the exact spelling of each word','Embeddings are random and carry no meaning','Embeddings only work for numbers, not words']::text[],0,ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::int[],'Embeddings map words to vectors so that semantically related words land near each other, which is why ''cat'' and ''kitten'' are close.','Embeddings map words to vectors so that semantically related words land near each other, which is why ''cat'' and ''kitten'' are close.','An embedding is a dense vector of numbers that represents a token or piece of text in a continuous space. Models learn these vectors so that items with similar meaning or usage sit near one another, letting distance and direction encode relationships. This is what lets systems compare meaning, power semantic search, and feed rich representations into transformers.','An embedding is a dense vector of numbers that represents a token or piece of text in a continuous space. Models learn these vectors so that items with similar meaning or usage sit near one another, letting distance and direction encode relationships. This is what lets systems compare meaning, power semantic search, and feed rich representations into transformers.',15,'approved','curated-taste');
INSERT INTO "BankQuestion" ("id","skillId","subareaKey","concept","difficulty","type","questionEn","questionPl","optionsEn","optionsPl","correctIndex","acceptedAnswers","orderItems","correctOrder","explanationEn","explanationPl","theoryEn","theoryPl","xp","qualityState","model") VALUES ('bank-ai-llms-3','ai','ai:llms','ai-llms-3','advanced','mcq','What key capability did the transformer''s self-attention mechanism introduce that helps models handle long-range relationships in text?','What key capability did the transformer''s self-attention mechanism introduce that helps models handle long-range relationships in text?',ARRAY['Each token can directly weigh and draw information from any other token in the sequence','It processes tokens strictly one at a time in fixed order with no parallelism','It removes the need for any training data','It guarantees the model never makes factual errors']::text[],ARRAY['Each token can directly weigh and draw information from any other token in the sequence','It processes tokens strictly one at a time in fixed order with no parallelism','It removes the need for any training data','It guarantees the model never makes factual errors']::text[],0,ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::int[],'Self-attention lets every token attend to every other token directly, capturing long-range dependencies that earlier sequential models struggled with.','Self-attention lets every token attend to every other token directly, capturing long-range dependencies that earlier sequential models struggled with.','The transformer architecture relies on self-attention, where each token computes how relevant every other token is and blends in their information accordingly. This direct any-to-any connectivity captures long-range context that older recurrent models handled poorly, and it parallelizes well across hardware. Self-attention is the backbone of modern large language models and a major reason they scale effectively.','The transformer architecture relies on self-attention, where each token computes how relevant every other token is and blends in their information accordingly. This direct any-to-any connectivity captures long-range context that older recurrent models handled poorly, and it parallelizes well across hardware. Self-attention is the backbone of modern large language models and a major reason they scale effectively.',25,'approved','curated-taste');
INSERT INTO "BankQuestion" ("id","skillId","subareaKey","concept","difficulty","type","questionEn","questionPl","optionsEn","optionsPl","correctIndex","acceptedAnswers","orderItems","correctOrder","explanationEn","explanationPl","theoryEn","theoryPl","xp","qualityState","model") VALUES ('bank-ai-prompting-1','ai','ai:prompting','ai-prompting-1','beginner','mcq','In a language model, raising the ''temperature'' setting generally has what effect on the generated text?','In a language model, raising the ''temperature'' setting generally has what effect on the generated text?',ARRAY['It makes outputs more random and varied','It makes outputs more repetitive and deterministic','It increases the model''s factual accuracy','It shortens the maximum response length']::text[],ARRAY['It makes outputs more random and varied','It makes outputs more repetitive and deterministic','It increases the model''s factual accuracy','It shortens the maximum response length']::text[],0,ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::int[],'Higher temperature flattens the probability distribution over next tokens, producing more random and diverse text.','Higher temperature flattens the probability distribution over next tokens, producing more random and diverse text.','Temperature is a sampling setting that controls how a model picks the next token from its predicted probabilities. Low temperature concentrates choices on the most likely tokens, giving focused and repeatable output, while high temperature spreads probability out, yielding more creative or surprising text. Choosing a value trades off reliability against variety depending on the task.','Temperature is a sampling setting that controls how a model picks the next token from its predicted probabilities. Low temperature concentrates choices on the most likely tokens, giving focused and repeatable output, while high temperature spreads probability out, yielding more creative or surprising text. Choosing a value trades off reliability against variety depending on the task.',10,'approved','curated-taste');
INSERT INTO "BankQuestion" ("id","skillId","subareaKey","concept","difficulty","type","questionEn","questionPl","optionsEn","optionsPl","correctIndex","acceptedAnswers","orderItems","correctOrder","explanationEn","explanationPl","theoryEn","theoryPl","xp","qualityState","model") VALUES ('bank-ai-prompting-2','ai','ai:prompting','ai-prompting-2','intermediate','mcq','A model confidently states a made-up citation that does not exist. In the context of language models, this behavior is best described as what?','A model confidently states a made-up citation that does not exist. In the context of language models, this behavior is best described as what?',ARRAY['A hallucination','A train-test split','An activation function','A clustering error']::text[],ARRAY['A hallucination','A train-test split','An activation function','A clustering error']::text[],0,ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::int[],'Generating fluent but false or fabricated information is known as hallucination in language models.','Generating fluent but false or fabricated information is known as hallucination in language models.','Hallucination is when a language model produces confident-sounding text that is factually wrong or entirely invented. It arises because the model predicts plausible continuations rather than retrieving verified facts. Grounding responses in trusted sources, asking for citations you can check, and evaluating outputs carefully all help reduce the impact of hallucinations.','Hallucination is when a language model produces confident-sounding text that is factually wrong or entirely invented. It arises because the model predicts plausible continuations rather than retrieving verified facts. Grounding responses in trusted sources, asking for citations you can check, and evaluating outputs carefully all help reduce the impact of hallucinations.',15,'approved','curated-taste');
INSERT INTO "BankQuestion" ("id","skillId","subareaKey","concept","difficulty","type","questionEn","questionPl","optionsEn","optionsPl","correctIndex","acceptedAnswers","orderItems","correctOrder","explanationEn","explanationPl","theoryEn","theoryPl","xp","qualityState","model") VALUES ('bank-ai-prompting-3','ai','ai:prompting','ai-prompting-3','advanced','mcq','A team adds retrieval-augmented generation (RAG) to their chatbot, which fits within the model''s limited context window. What primary benefit does RAG provide?','A team adds retrieval-augmented generation (RAG) to their chatbot, which fits within the model''s limited context window. What primary benefit does RAG provide?',ARRAY['It supplies relevant external documents at query time so answers are grounded in current, specific information','It permanently retrains the model''s weights on every user question','It removes the need to evaluate the system''s outputs','It eliminates the model''s context window limit entirely']::text[],ARRAY['It supplies relevant external documents at query time so answers are grounded in current, specific information','It permanently retrains the model''s weights on every user question','It removes the need to evaluate the system''s outputs','It eliminates the model''s context window limit entirely']::text[],0,ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::int[],'RAG retrieves relevant documents and inserts them into the prompt so the model can ground answers in external, up-to-date information without retraining.','RAG retrieves relevant documents and inserts them into the prompt so the model can ground answers in external, up-to-date information without retraining.','Retrieval-augmented generation pairs a language model with a search step that fetches relevant text from an external knowledge source and adds it to the prompt. This grounds responses in specific or current information the model was not trained on, reducing hallucination. Because models have a finite context window, retrieval must select only the most relevant passages, and outputs should still be evaluated for accuracy.','Retrieval-augmented generation pairs a language model with a search step that fetches relevant text from an external knowledge source and adds it to the prompt. This grounds responses in specific or current information the model was not trained on, reducing hallucination. Because models have a finite context window, retrieval must select only the most relevant passages, and outputs should still be evaluated for accuracy.',25,'approved','curated-taste');
INSERT INTO "BankQuestion" ("id","skillId","subareaKey","concept","difficulty","type","questionEn","questionPl","optionsEn","optionsPl","correctIndex","acceptedAnswers","orderItems","correctOrder","explanationEn","explanationPl","theoryEn","theoryPl","xp","qualityState","model") VALUES ('bankq-ai-ml-b-1','ai','ai:ml','ai-ml-b-1','beginner','mcq','In machine learning, what distinguishes supervised learning from unsupervised learning?','In machine learning, what distinguishes supervised learning from unsupervised learning?',ARRAY['Supervised learning trains on labeled examples, while unsupervised learning finds structure in unlabeled data','Supervised learning requires a human to watch the model run at all times','Unsupervised learning always produces more accurate predictions than supervised learning','Supervised learning can only be used for images, unsupervised only for text']::text[],ARRAY['Supervised learning trains on labeled examples, while unsupervised learning finds structure in unlabeled data','Supervised learning requires a human to watch the model run at all times','Unsupervised learning always produces more accurate predictions than supervised learning','Supervised learning can only be used for images, unsupervised only for text']::text[],0,ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::int[],'Supervised learning uses input-output pairs with known labels, whereas unsupervised learning discovers patterns such as clusters in data that has no labels.','Supervised learning uses input-output pairs with known labels, whereas unsupervised learning discovers patterns such as clusters in data that has no labels.','Supervised learning learns a mapping from inputs to known target labels, as in classifying emails as spam or not. Unsupervised learning works on data without labels and instead uncovers hidden structure, such as grouping similar customers together. The key difference is whether the correct answers are provided during training.','Supervised learning learns a mapping from inputs to known target labels, as in classifying emails as spam or not. Unsupervised learning works on data without labels and instead uncovers hidden structure, such as grouping similar customers together. The key difference is whether the correct answers are provided during training.',10,'approved','curated-bank');
INSERT INTO "BankQuestion" ("id","skillId","subareaKey","concept","difficulty","type","questionEn","questionPl","optionsEn","optionsPl","correctIndex","acceptedAnswers","orderItems","correctOrder","explanationEn","explanationPl","theoryEn","theoryPl","xp","qualityState","model") VALUES ('bankq-ai-ml-b-2','ai','ai:ml','ai-ml-b-2','beginner','truefalse','True or false: A classification task predicts a discrete category label, while a regression task predicts a continuous numeric value.','True or false: A classification task predicts a discrete category label, while a regression task predicts a continuous numeric value.',ARRAY['True','False']::text[],ARRAY['True','False']::text[],0,ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::int[],'Classification outputs categories such as cat or dog, whereas regression outputs continuous numbers such as a predicted price.','Classification outputs categories such as cat or dog, whereas regression outputs continuous numbers such as a predicted price.','Classification and regression are the two main types of supervised learning problems. Classification assigns inputs to one of a fixed set of classes, like spam versus not spam. Regression predicts a real-valued quantity, such as tomorrow''s temperature or a house price.','Classification and regression are the two main types of supervised learning problems. Classification assigns inputs to one of a fixed set of classes, like spam versus not spam. Regression predicts a real-valued quantity, such as tomorrow''s temperature or a house price.',10,'approved','curated-bank');
INSERT INTO "BankQuestion" ("id","skillId","subareaKey","concept","difficulty","type","questionEn","questionPl","optionsEn","optionsPl","correctIndex","acceptedAnswers","orderItems","correctOrder","explanationEn","explanationPl","theoryEn","theoryPl","xp","qualityState","model") VALUES ('bankq-ai-ml-i-1','ai','ai:ml','ai-ml-i-1','intermediate','mcq','A model achieves 99% accuracy on training data but only 70% on new test data. What is the most likely problem?','A model achieves 99% accuracy on training data but only 70% on new test data. What is the most likely problem?',ARRAY['Overfitting: the model memorized training noise and fails to generalize','Underfitting: the model is too simple to capture the data','The test set is guaranteed to be corrupted','The learning rate must be set to exactly zero']::text[],ARRAY['Overfitting: the model memorized training noise and fails to generalize','Underfitting: the model is too simple to capture the data','The test set is guaranteed to be corrupted','The learning rate must be set to exactly zero']::text[],0,ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::int[],'A large gap between high training accuracy and lower test accuracy is the classic signature of overfitting.','A large gap between high training accuracy and lower test accuracy is the classic signature of overfitting.','Overfitting happens when a model fits the training data so closely that it captures noise and idiosyncrasies rather than the underlying pattern. Such a model performs well on data it has seen but poorly on new data. Techniques like regularization, more data, and simpler models help improve generalization.','Overfitting happens when a model fits the training data so closely that it captures noise and idiosyncrasies rather than the underlying pattern. Such a model performs well on data it has seen but poorly on new data. Techniques like regularization, more data, and simpler models help improve generalization.',15,'approved','curated-bank');
INSERT INTO "BankQuestion" ("id","skillId","subareaKey","concept","difficulty","type","questionEn","questionPl","optionsEn","optionsPl","correctIndex","acceptedAnswers","orderItems","correctOrder","explanationEn","explanationPl","theoryEn","theoryPl","xp","qualityState","model") VALUES ('bankq-ai-ml-i-2','ai','ai:ml','ai-ml-i-2','intermediate','mcq','Why is data typically split into separate training and test sets before evaluating a model?','Why is data typically split into separate training and test sets before evaluating a model?',ARRAY['To estimate how well the model generalizes to unseen data rather than data it memorized','To make training run faster by using fewer examples overall','Because models can only read data that has been split into two files','To guarantee the model will reach 100% accuracy on the training set']::text[],ARRAY['To estimate how well the model generalizes to unseen data rather than data it memorized','To make training run faster by using fewer examples overall','Because models can only read data that has been split into two files','To guarantee the model will reach 100% accuracy on the training set']::text[],0,ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::int[],'Holding out a test set gives an honest estimate of performance on data the model never saw during training.','Holding out a test set gives an honest estimate of performance on data the model never saw during training.','If a model is evaluated on the same data it trained on, the score is overly optimistic because the model may have memorized those examples. A held-out test set simulates new, unseen data and provides a fairer measure of generalization. A separate validation set is often used as well to tune hyperparameters without touching the test set.','If a model is evaluated on the same data it trained on, the score is overly optimistic because the model may have memorized those examples. A held-out test set simulates new, unseen data and provides a fairer measure of generalization. A separate validation set is often used as well to tune hyperparameters without touching the test set.',15,'approved','curated-bank');
INSERT INTO "BankQuestion" ("id","skillId","subareaKey","concept","difficulty","type","questionEn","questionPl","optionsEn","optionsPl","correctIndex","acceptedAnswers","orderItems","correctOrder","explanationEn","explanationPl","theoryEn","theoryPl","xp","qualityState","model") VALUES ('bankq-ai-ml-a-1','ai','ai:ml','ai-ml-a-1','advanced','mcq','In the context of the bias-variance tradeoff, what characterizes a model with high variance?','In the context of the bias-variance tradeoff, what characterizes a model with high variance?',ARRAY['It is very sensitive to the specific training data and tends to overfit','It is too rigid and underfits regardless of the data','It always has lower test error than any low-variance model','It ignores the training data entirely and predicts constants']::text[],ARRAY['It is very sensitive to the specific training data and tends to overfit','It is too rigid and underfits regardless of the data','It always has lower test error than any low-variance model','It ignores the training data entirely and predicts constants']::text[],0,ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::int[],'High variance means the model changes a lot with different training samples, capturing noise and overfitting.','High variance means the model changes a lot with different training samples, capturing noise and overfitting.','The bias-variance tradeoff describes two sources of error. High bias means the model is too simple and systematically misses the pattern (underfitting). High variance means the model is too flexible and reacts strongly to fluctuations in the training data (overfitting). Good generalization requires balancing the two.','The bias-variance tradeoff describes two sources of error. High bias means the model is too simple and systematically misses the pattern (underfitting). High variance means the model is too flexible and reacts strongly to fluctuations in the training data (overfitting). Good generalization requires balancing the two.',25,'approved','curated-bank');
INSERT INTO "BankQuestion" ("id","skillId","subareaKey","concept","difficulty","type","questionEn","questionPl","optionsEn","optionsPl","correctIndex","acceptedAnswers","orderItems","correctOrder","explanationEn","explanationPl","theoryEn","theoryPl","xp","qualityState","model") VALUES ('bankq-ai-ml-a-2','ai','ai:ml','ai-ml-a-2','advanced','mcq','When using k-fold cross-validation, what is the primary benefit over a single train-test split?','When using k-fold cross-validation, what is the primary benefit over a single train-test split?',ARRAY['It uses every data point for both training and validation across folds, giving a more reliable performance estimate','It eliminates the need for any test data at all','It always increases the model''s training accuracy to 100%','It removes the need to choose any hyperparameters']::text[],ARRAY['It uses every data point for both training and validation across folds, giving a more reliable performance estimate','It eliminates the need for any test data at all','It always increases the model''s training accuracy to 100%','It removes the need to choose any hyperparameters']::text[],0,ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::int[],'Cross-validation rotates the validation fold so the estimate is averaged over multiple splits, reducing dependence on one lucky or unlucky split.','Cross-validation rotates the validation fold so the estimate is averaged over multiple splits, reducing dependence on one lucky or unlucky split.','In k-fold cross-validation the data is partitioned into k folds; the model is trained k times, each time holding out a different fold for validation. Averaging the results gives a more stable estimate of performance than a single split, especially with limited data. It is particularly useful for comparing models and tuning hyperparameters.','In k-fold cross-validation the data is partitioned into k folds; the model is trained k times, each time holding out a different fold for validation. Averaging the results gives a more stable estimate of performance than a single split, especially with limited data. It is particularly useful for comparing models and tuning hyperparameters.',25,'approved','curated-bank');
INSERT INTO "BankQuestion" ("id","skillId","subareaKey","concept","difficulty","type","questionEn","questionPl","optionsEn","optionsPl","correctIndex","acceptedAnswers","orderItems","correctOrder","explanationEn","explanationPl","theoryEn","theoryPl","xp","qualityState","model") VALUES ('bankq-ai-neural-b-1','ai','ai:neural','ai-neural-b-1','beginner','mcq','What is the role of an activation function in a neural network?','What is the role of an activation function in a neural network?',ARRAY['It introduces non-linearity so the network can model complex relationships','It stores the training data inside each neuron','It guarantees the network never makes mistakes','It converts the network into a single linear equation']::text[],ARRAY['It introduces non-linearity so the network can model complex relationships','It stores the training data inside each neuron','It guarantees the network never makes mistakes','It converts the network into a single linear equation']::text[],0,ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::int[],'Non-linear activation functions let stacked layers represent complex, non-linear functions instead of collapsing into one linear transformation.','Non-linear activation functions let stacked layers represent complex, non-linear functions instead of collapsing into one linear transformation.','Each neuron computes a weighted sum of its inputs and then applies an activation function. Without a non-linear activation, stacking many layers would still only produce a linear function. Non-linear activations such as ReLU or sigmoid give networks the power to approximate complicated patterns.','Each neuron computes a weighted sum of its inputs and then applies an activation function. Without a non-linear activation, stacking many layers would still only produce a linear function. Non-linear activations such as ReLU or sigmoid give networks the power to approximate complicated patterns.',10,'approved','curated-bank');
INSERT INTO "BankQuestion" ("id","skillId","subareaKey","concept","difficulty","type","questionEn","questionPl","optionsEn","optionsPl","correctIndex","acceptedAnswers","orderItems","correctOrder","explanationEn","explanationPl","theoryEn","theoryPl","xp","qualityState","model") VALUES ('bankq-ai-neural-b-2','ai','ai:neural','ai-neural-b-2','beginner','truefalse','True or false: A neuron in a neural network computes a weighted sum of its inputs and then applies an activation function to that sum.','True or false: A neuron in a neural network computes a weighted sum of its inputs and then applies an activation function to that sum.',ARRAY['True','False']::text[],ARRAY['True','False']::text[],0,ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::int[],'Each neuron multiplies inputs by weights, adds a bias, and passes the result through an activation function.','Each neuron multiplies inputs by weights, adds a bias, and passes the result through an activation function.','An artificial neuron takes several inputs, multiplies each by a learned weight, and adds them together along with a bias term. The resulting value is fed through an activation function to produce the neuron''s output. Connecting many such neurons in layers forms a neural network.','An artificial neuron takes several inputs, multiplies each by a learned weight, and adds them together along with a bias term. The resulting value is fed through an activation function to produce the neuron''s output. Connecting many such neurons in layers forms a neural network.',10,'approved','curated-bank');
INSERT INTO "BankQuestion" ("id","skillId","subareaKey","concept","difficulty","type","questionEn","questionPl","optionsEn","optionsPl","correctIndex","acceptedAnswers","orderItems","correctOrder","explanationEn","explanationPl","theoryEn","theoryPl","xp","qualityState","model") VALUES ('bankq-ai-neural-i-1','ai','ai:neural','ai-neural-i-1','intermediate','mcq','What does the backpropagation algorithm compute during neural network training?','What does the backpropagation algorithm compute during neural network training?',ARRAY['The gradient of the loss with respect to each weight, used to update the weights','The final accuracy of the model on the test set','A random reshuffling of the training examples','The number of neurons that should be added to each layer']::text[],ARRAY['The gradient of the loss with respect to each weight, used to update the weights','The final accuracy of the model on the test set','A random reshuffling of the training examples','The number of neurons that should be added to each layer']::text[],0,ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::int[],'Backpropagation applies the chain rule to efficiently compute how the loss changes with each weight, enabling gradient-based updates.','Backpropagation applies the chain rule to efficiently compute how the loss changes with each weight, enabling gradient-based updates.','Backpropagation propagates the error from the output layer back through the network using the chain rule of calculus. This yields the gradient of the loss with respect to every weight. An optimizer like gradient descent then nudges each weight in the direction that reduces the loss.','Backpropagation propagates the error from the output layer back through the network using the chain rule of calculus. This yields the gradient of the loss with respect to every weight. An optimizer like gradient descent then nudges each weight in the direction that reduces the loss.',15,'approved','curated-bank');
INSERT INTO "BankQuestion" ("id","skillId","subareaKey","concept","difficulty","type","questionEn","questionPl","optionsEn","optionsPl","correctIndex","acceptedAnswers","orderItems","correctOrder","explanationEn","explanationPl","theoryEn","theoryPl","xp","qualityState","model") VALUES ('bankq-ai-neural-i-2','ai','ai:neural','ai-neural-i-2','intermediate','mcq','In gradient descent, what is the purpose of the learning rate?','In gradient descent, what is the purpose of the learning rate?',ARRAY['It controls the step size taken when updating weights along the gradient','It sets the number of layers in the network','It determines how many output classes the model has','It measures the accuracy of the model directly']::text[],ARRAY['It controls the step size taken when updating weights along the gradient','It sets the number of layers in the network','It determines how many output classes the model has','It measures the accuracy of the model directly']::text[],0,ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::int[],'The learning rate scales how far weights move on each update; too large can overshoot, too small can be slow.','The learning rate scales how far weights move on each update; too large can overshoot, too small can be slow.','Gradient descent updates weights by moving them opposite to the gradient of the loss. The learning rate is a hyperparameter that multiplies the gradient to decide the size of each step. A rate that is too high can cause the loss to diverge, while one that is too low makes training painfully slow.','Gradient descent updates weights by moving them opposite to the gradient of the loss. The learning rate is a hyperparameter that multiplies the gradient to decide the size of each step. A rate that is too high can cause the loss to diverge, while one that is too low makes training painfully slow.',15,'approved','curated-bank');
INSERT INTO "BankQuestion" ("id","skillId","subareaKey","concept","difficulty","type","questionEn","questionPl","optionsEn","optionsPl","correctIndex","acceptedAnswers","orderItems","correctOrder","explanationEn","explanationPl","theoryEn","theoryPl","xp","qualityState","model") VALUES ('bankq-ai-neural-a-1','ai','ai:neural','ai-neural-a-1','advanced','mcq','Why is the ReLU activation function often preferred over sigmoid in deep networks?','Why is the ReLU activation function often preferred over sigmoid in deep networks?',ARRAY['ReLU does not saturate for positive inputs, helping mitigate the vanishing gradient problem','ReLU always outputs values between 0 and 1 like a probability','ReLU has no derivative anywhere, which speeds up training','ReLU guarantees the network cannot overfit']::text[],ARRAY['ReLU does not saturate for positive inputs, helping mitigate the vanishing gradient problem','ReLU always outputs values between 0 and 1 like a probability','ReLU has no derivative anywhere, which speeds up training','ReLU guarantees the network cannot overfit']::text[],0,ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::int[],'Sigmoid gradients shrink toward zero for large-magnitude inputs, whereas ReLU keeps a constant gradient of 1 for positive inputs, easing gradient flow in deep nets.','Sigmoid gradients shrink toward zero for large-magnitude inputs, whereas ReLU keeps a constant gradient of 1 for positive inputs, easing gradient flow in deep nets.','The vanishing gradient problem occurs when gradients become extremely small as they propagate back through many layers, stalling learning. Sigmoid and tanh saturate at their extremes, producing tiny gradients. ReLU keeps a gradient of 1 for positive inputs, allowing gradients to flow more effectively through deep networks.','The vanishing gradient problem occurs when gradients become extremely small as they propagate back through many layers, stalling learning. Sigmoid and tanh saturate at their extremes, producing tiny gradients. ReLU keeps a gradient of 1 for positive inputs, allowing gradients to flow more effectively through deep networks.',25,'approved','curated-bank');
INSERT INTO "BankQuestion" ("id","skillId","subareaKey","concept","difficulty","type","questionEn","questionPl","optionsEn","optionsPl","correctIndex","acceptedAnswers","orderItems","correctOrder","explanationEn","explanationPl","theoryEn","theoryPl","xp","qualityState","model") VALUES ('bankq-ai-neural-a-2','ai','ai:neural','ai-neural-a-2','advanced','mcq','What problem does dropout primarily address during neural network training?','What problem does dropout primarily address during neural network training?',ARRAY['Overfitting, by randomly deactivating neurons so the network cannot rely on any single one','Slow data loading from disk during each epoch','The need to compute gradients at all','Choosing the optimal number of output classes']::text[],ARRAY['Overfitting, by randomly deactivating neurons so the network cannot rely on any single one','Slow data loading from disk during each epoch','The need to compute gradients at all','Choosing the optimal number of output classes']::text[],0,ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::int[],'Dropout randomly zeros out neurons during training, forcing redundancy and acting as a regularizer that reduces overfitting.','Dropout randomly zeros out neurons during training, forcing redundancy and acting as a regularizer that reduces overfitting.','Dropout is a regularization technique where, during each training step, a random subset of neurons is temporarily turned off. This prevents the network from becoming overly dependent on specific neurons and encourages more robust, distributed representations. At inference time all neurons are used, with activations scaled appropriately.','Dropout is a regularization technique where, during each training step, a random subset of neurons is temporarily turned off. This prevents the network from becoming overly dependent on specific neurons and encourages more robust, distributed representations. At inference time all neurons are used, with activations scaled appropriately.',25,'approved','curated-bank');
INSERT INTO "BankQuestion" ("id","skillId","subareaKey","concept","difficulty","type","questionEn","questionPl","optionsEn","optionsPl","correctIndex","acceptedAnswers","orderItems","correctOrder","explanationEn","explanationPl","theoryEn","theoryPl","xp","qualityState","model") VALUES ('bankq-ai-llms-b-1','ai','ai:llms','ai-llms-b-1','beginner','mcq','In a large language model, what is a token?','In a large language model, what is a token?',ARRAY['A chunk of text, often a word or sub-word piece, that the model processes as a unit','A password that unlocks the model','A single pixel in an input image','The name of the optimizer used during training']::text[],ARRAY['A chunk of text, often a word or sub-word piece, that the model processes as a unit','A password that unlocks the model','A single pixel in an input image','The name of the optimizer used during training']::text[],0,ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::int[],'Text is broken into tokens (words or sub-word fragments) which are the basic units the model reads and predicts.','Text is broken into tokens (words or sub-word fragments) which are the basic units the model reads and predicts.','Language models do not read raw characters directly; instead text is split into tokens by a tokenizer. A token may be a whole word, a sub-word fragment, or punctuation. The model processes sequences of tokens and predicts the next token, and usage and context limits are measured in tokens.','Language models do not read raw characters directly; instead text is split into tokens by a tokenizer. A token may be a whole word, a sub-word fragment, or punctuation. The model processes sequences of tokens and predicts the next token, and usage and context limits are measured in tokens.',10,'approved','curated-bank');
INSERT INTO "BankQuestion" ("id","skillId","subareaKey","concept","difficulty","type","questionEn","questionPl","optionsEn","optionsPl","correctIndex","acceptedAnswers","orderItems","correctOrder","explanationEn","explanationPl","theoryEn","theoryPl","xp","qualityState","model") VALUES ('bankq-ai-llms-b-2','ai','ai:llms','ai-llms-b-2','beginner','truefalse','True or false: An embedding represents a token or piece of text as a vector of numbers that captures aspects of its meaning.','True or false: An embedding represents a token or piece of text as a vector of numbers that captures aspects of its meaning.',ARRAY['True','False']::text[],ARRAY['True','False']::text[],0,ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::int[],'Embeddings map tokens or text into numeric vectors where similar meanings tend to be located close together.','Embeddings map tokens or text into numeric vectors where similar meanings tend to be located close together.','An embedding is a dense vector of real numbers that represents a token, word, or chunk of text. These vectors are learned so that items with similar meaning or usage end up near each other in the vector space. Embeddings let models and search systems reason about semantic similarity numerically.','An embedding is a dense vector of real numbers that represents a token, word, or chunk of text. These vectors are learned so that items with similar meaning or usage end up near each other in the vector space. Embeddings let models and search systems reason about semantic similarity numerically.',10,'approved','curated-bank');
INSERT INTO "BankQuestion" ("id","skillId","subareaKey","concept","difficulty","type","questionEn","questionPl","optionsEn","optionsPl","correctIndex","acceptedAnswers","orderItems","correctOrder","explanationEn","explanationPl","theoryEn","theoryPl","xp","qualityState","model") VALUES ('bankq-ai-llms-i-1','ai','ai:llms','ai-llms-i-1','intermediate','mcq','What core mechanism in the transformer architecture lets a model weigh the relevance of different tokens to each other?','What core mechanism in the transformer architecture lets a model weigh the relevance of different tokens to each other?',ARRAY['Self-attention','Max pooling','A single fixed convolution filter','Manual keyword matching']::text[],ARRAY['Self-attention','Max pooling','A single fixed convolution filter','Manual keyword matching']::text[],0,ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::int[],'Self-attention lets each token attend to and incorporate information from other tokens based on learned relevance scores.','Self-attention lets each token attend to and incorporate information from other tokens based on learned relevance scores.','Transformers, introduced in 2017, rely on the self-attention mechanism to relate tokens within a sequence. For each token, attention computes weighted combinations of other tokens based on their relevance. This lets the model capture long-range dependencies and context far more flexibly than older recurrent approaches.','Transformers, introduced in 2017, rely on the self-attention mechanism to relate tokens within a sequence. For each token, attention computes weighted combinations of other tokens based on their relevance. This lets the model capture long-range dependencies and context far more flexibly than older recurrent approaches.',15,'approved','curated-bank');
INSERT INTO "BankQuestion" ("id","skillId","subareaKey","concept","difficulty","type","questionEn","questionPl","optionsEn","optionsPl","correctIndex","acceptedAnswers","orderItems","correctOrder","explanationEn","explanationPl","theoryEn","theoryPl","xp","qualityState","model") VALUES ('bankq-ai-llms-i-2','ai','ai:llms','ai-llms-i-2','intermediate','mcq','What does a language model''s context window refer to?','What does a language model''s context window refer to?',ARRAY['The maximum amount of text, measured in tokens, the model can consider at once','The screen resolution required to display the model''s output','The number of parameters in the model','The time of day the model is allowed to run']::text[],ARRAY['The maximum amount of text, measured in tokens, the model can consider at once','The screen resolution required to display the model''s output','The number of parameters in the model','The time of day the model is allowed to run']::text[],0,ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::int[],'The context window is the token limit for the combined prompt and generated output that the model can attend to in a single pass.','The context window is the token limit for the combined prompt and generated output that the model can attend to in a single pass.','The context window is the maximum number of tokens a model can process together, including the prompt and its response. Text beyond this limit must be truncated, summarized, or otherwise handled. Larger context windows let models work with longer documents and conversations, but they increase computational cost.','The context window is the maximum number of tokens a model can process together, including the prompt and its response. Text beyond this limit must be truncated, summarized, or otherwise handled. Larger context windows let models work with longer documents and conversations, but they increase computational cost.',15,'approved','curated-bank');
INSERT INTO "BankQuestion" ("id","skillId","subareaKey","concept","difficulty","type","questionEn","questionPl","optionsEn","optionsPl","correctIndex","acceptedAnswers","orderItems","correctOrder","explanationEn","explanationPl","theoryEn","theoryPl","xp","qualityState","model") VALUES ('bankq-ai-llms-a-1','ai','ai:llms','ai-llms-a-1','advanced','mcq','What is the main purpose of Retrieval-Augmented Generation (RAG)?','What is the main purpose of Retrieval-Augmented Generation (RAG)?',ARRAY['To fetch relevant external documents at query time and feed them into the prompt so answers are grounded in that information','To permanently retrain the model''s weights on each new question','To compress the model so it runs on smaller hardware','To remove the need for any prompt at all']::text[],ARRAY['To fetch relevant external documents at query time and feed them into the prompt so answers are grounded in that information','To permanently retrain the model''s weights on each new question','To compress the model so it runs on smaller hardware','To remove the need for any prompt at all']::text[],0,ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::int[],'RAG retrieves relevant text from an external knowledge source and supplies it as context, grounding responses without retraining the model.','RAG retrieves relevant text from an external knowledge source and supplies it as context, grounding responses without retraining the model.','Retrieval-Augmented Generation combines a retrieval step with generation. When a query arrives, relevant documents are fetched from a knowledge base, often using embedding-based similarity search, and inserted into the model''s context. This grounds answers in up-to-date or proprietary information and can reduce hallucination without modifying the model''s weights.','Retrieval-Augmented Generation combines a retrieval step with generation. When a query arrives, relevant documents are fetched from a knowledge base, often using embedding-based similarity search, and inserted into the model''s context. This grounds answers in up-to-date or proprietary information and can reduce hallucination without modifying the model''s weights.',25,'approved','curated-bank');
INSERT INTO "BankQuestion" ("id","skillId","subareaKey","concept","difficulty","type","questionEn","questionPl","optionsEn","optionsPl","correctIndex","acceptedAnswers","orderItems","correctOrder","explanationEn","explanationPl","theoryEn","theoryPl","xp","qualityState","model") VALUES ('bankq-ai-llms-a-2','ai','ai:llms','ai-llms-a-2','advanced','mcq','In the context of large language models, what does the term hallucination describe?','In the context of large language models, what does the term hallucination describe?',ARRAY['When the model produces fluent, confident output that is factually incorrect or unsupported','When the model refuses to answer any question','When the model runs out of memory and crashes','When the model only outputs text it has copied verbatim from training data']::text[],ARRAY['When the model produces fluent, confident output that is factually incorrect or unsupported','When the model refuses to answer any question','When the model runs out of memory and crashes','When the model only outputs text it has copied verbatim from training data']::text[],0,ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::int[],'A hallucination is plausible-sounding but false or fabricated content generated by the model.','A hallucination is plausible-sounding but false or fabricated content generated by the model.','Language models generate text by predicting likely token sequences, not by looking up verified facts. As a result they can produce confident statements that are wrong or invented, known as hallucinations. Grounding techniques like RAG, citation, and careful evaluation help detect and reduce them.','Language models generate text by predicting likely token sequences, not by looking up verified facts. As a result they can produce confident statements that are wrong or invented, known as hallucinations. Grounding techniques like RAG, citation, and careful evaluation help detect and reduce them.',25,'approved','curated-bank');
INSERT INTO "BankQuestion" ("id","skillId","subareaKey","concept","difficulty","type","questionEn","questionPl","optionsEn","optionsPl","correctIndex","acceptedAnswers","orderItems","correctOrder","explanationEn","explanationPl","theoryEn","theoryPl","xp","qualityState","model") VALUES ('bankq-ai-prompting-b-1','ai','ai:prompting','ai-prompting-b-1','beginner','mcq','What does few-shot prompting mean?','What does few-shot prompting mean?',ARRAY['Including a few example input-output pairs in the prompt to guide the model''s response','Running the model only a few times per day','Training the model from scratch on a few images','Limiting the model to answers of a few words']::text[],ARRAY['Including a few example input-output pairs in the prompt to guide the model''s response','Running the model only a few times per day','Training the model from scratch on a few images','Limiting the model to answers of a few words']::text[],0,ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::int[],'Few-shot prompting provides several worked examples in the prompt so the model can infer the desired pattern.','Few-shot prompting provides several worked examples in the prompt so the model can infer the desired pattern.','Few-shot prompting gives the model a handful of examples demonstrating the task within the prompt itself. The model uses these examples to infer the expected format and behavior, without any change to its weights. Zero-shot prompting, by contrast, provides instructions but no examples.','Few-shot prompting gives the model a handful of examples demonstrating the task within the prompt itself. The model uses these examples to infer the expected format and behavior, without any change to its weights. Zero-shot prompting, by contrast, provides instructions but no examples.',10,'approved','curated-bank');
INSERT INTO "BankQuestion" ("id","skillId","subareaKey","concept","difficulty","type","questionEn","questionPl","optionsEn","optionsPl","correctIndex","acceptedAnswers","orderItems","correctOrder","explanationEn","explanationPl","theoryEn","theoryPl","xp","qualityState","model") VALUES ('bankq-ai-prompting-b-2','ai','ai:prompting','ai-prompting-b-2','beginner','mcq','When sampling from a language model, what does a higher temperature setting generally do?','When sampling from a language model, what does a higher temperature setting generally do?',ARRAY['Makes the output more random and varied','Makes the output strictly shorter','Forces the model to always pick the single most likely token','Disables the model''s ability to generate text']::text[],ARRAY['Makes the output more random and varied','Makes the output strictly shorter','Forces the model to always pick the single most likely token','Disables the model''s ability to generate text']::text[],0,ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::int[],'Higher temperature flattens the probability distribution over tokens, increasing randomness and diversity in the output.','Higher temperature flattens the probability distribution over tokens, increasing randomness and diversity in the output.','Temperature is a sampling parameter that scales the model''s token probabilities before selection. Low temperature makes the model favor the most probable tokens, producing focused and deterministic text. High temperature spreads probability more evenly, yielding more diverse and creative but less predictable output.','Temperature is a sampling parameter that scales the model''s token probabilities before selection. Low temperature makes the model favor the most probable tokens, producing focused and deterministic text. High temperature spreads probability more evenly, yielding more diverse and creative but less predictable output.',10,'approved','curated-bank');
INSERT INTO "BankQuestion" ("id","skillId","subareaKey","concept","difficulty","type","questionEn","questionPl","optionsEn","optionsPl","correctIndex","acceptedAnswers","orderItems","correctOrder","explanationEn","explanationPl","theoryEn","theoryPl","xp","qualityState","model") VALUES ('bankq-ai-prompting-i-1','ai','ai:prompting','ai-prompting-i-1','intermediate','mcq','What is the main idea behind chain-of-thought prompting?','What is the main idea behind chain-of-thought prompting?',ARRAY['Encouraging the model to generate intermediate reasoning steps before giving a final answer','Chaining several different models together in a pipeline','Forcing the model to answer in a single word','Hiding all instructions from the model']::text[],ARRAY['Encouraging the model to generate intermediate reasoning steps before giving a final answer','Chaining several different models together in a pipeline','Forcing the model to answer in a single word','Hiding all instructions from the model']::text[],0,ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::int[],'Chain-of-thought prompting asks the model to reason step by step, which often improves accuracy on multi-step problems.','Chain-of-thought prompting asks the model to reason step by step, which often improves accuracy on multi-step problems.','Chain-of-thought prompting instructs or shows the model to work through a problem in explicit intermediate steps rather than jumping straight to an answer. This tends to improve performance on tasks that require arithmetic, logic, or multi-step reasoning. The reasoning trace also makes the model''s process more transparent and easier to check.','Chain-of-thought prompting instructs or shows the model to work through a problem in explicit intermediate steps rather than jumping straight to an answer. This tends to improve performance on tasks that require arithmetic, logic, or multi-step reasoning. The reasoning trace also makes the model''s process more transparent and easier to check.',15,'approved','curated-bank');
INSERT INTO "BankQuestion" ("id","skillId","subareaKey","concept","difficulty","type","questionEn","questionPl","optionsEn","optionsPl","correctIndex","acceptedAnswers","orderItems","correctOrder","explanationEn","explanationPl","theoryEn","theoryPl","xp","qualityState","model") VALUES ('bankq-ai-prompting-i-2','ai','ai:prompting','ai-prompting-i-2','intermediate','truefalse','True or false: Setting temperature to 0 makes a language model''s sampling effectively deterministic, usually selecting the most probable next token each time.','True or false: Setting temperature to 0 makes a language model''s sampling effectively deterministic, usually selecting the most probable next token each time.',ARRAY['True','False']::text[],ARRAY['True','False']::text[],0,ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::int[],'At temperature 0 the model greedily picks the highest-probability token, so for a given prompt the output is essentially deterministic.','At temperature 0 the model greedily picks the highest-probability token, so for a given prompt the output is essentially deterministic.','Temperature controls randomness in token sampling. As temperature approaches 0, the distribution collapses onto the single most likely token, a strategy known as greedy decoding. This produces consistent, repeatable output, which is useful when you want reliable answers rather than creative variety.','Temperature controls randomness in token sampling. As temperature approaches 0, the distribution collapses onto the single most likely token, a strategy known as greedy decoding. This produces consistent, repeatable output, which is useful when you want reliable answers rather than creative variety.',15,'approved','curated-bank');
INSERT INTO "BankQuestion" ("id","skillId","subareaKey","concept","difficulty","type","questionEn","questionPl","optionsEn","optionsPl","correctIndex","acceptedAnswers","orderItems","correctOrder","explanationEn","explanationPl","theoryEn","theoryPl","xp","qualityState","model") VALUES ('bankq-ai-prompting-a-1','ai','ai:prompting','ai-prompting-a-1','advanced','mcq','When evaluating an LLM on an open-ended generation task, why is exact-match accuracy against a single reference often a poor metric?','When evaluating an LLM on an open-ended generation task, why is exact-match accuracy against a single reference often a poor metric?',ARRAY['Many different responses can be equally correct, so a single reference unfairly penalizes valid variations','Exact-match always overestimates model quality','Open-ended tasks have no correct answers at all','Exact-match can only be used for images']::text[],ARRAY['Many different responses can be equally correct, so a single reference unfairly penalizes valid variations','Exact-match always overestimates model quality','Open-ended tasks have no correct answers at all','Exact-match can only be used for images']::text[],0,ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::int[],'Open-ended tasks admit many valid wordings, so requiring an exact string match misses correct answers phrased differently.','Open-ended tasks admit many valid wordings, so requiring an exact string match misses correct answers phrased differently.','For open-ended generation there is rarely one right answer; correct responses can vary in wording, structure, and detail. Exact-match scoring against a single reference therefore underestimates quality. Better approaches include human evaluation, rubric-based grading, semantic similarity, or using a strong model as a judge.','For open-ended generation there is rarely one right answer; correct responses can vary in wording, structure, and detail. Exact-match scoring against a single reference therefore underestimates quality. Better approaches include human evaluation, rubric-based grading, semantic similarity, or using a strong model as a judge.',25,'approved','curated-bank');
INSERT INTO "BankQuestion" ("id","skillId","subareaKey","concept","difficulty","type","questionEn","questionPl","optionsEn","optionsPl","correctIndex","acceptedAnswers","orderItems","correctOrder","explanationEn","explanationPl","theoryEn","theoryPl","xp","qualityState","model") VALUES ('bankq-ai-prompting-a-2','ai','ai:prompting','ai-prompting-a-2','advanced','mcq','What is a key risk when using an LLM as an automated judge to evaluate other models'' outputs?','What is a key risk when using an LLM as an automated judge to evaluate other models'' outputs?',ARRAY['The judge can carry its own biases, such as favoring longer or more confident answers regardless of correctness','The judge is mathematically guaranteed to be perfectly accurate','The judge cannot read text at all','Using an LLM judge removes all need for any reference answers, with no downsides']::text[],ARRAY['The judge can carry its own biases, such as favoring longer or more confident answers regardless of correctness','The judge is mathematically guaranteed to be perfectly accurate','The judge cannot read text at all','Using an LLM judge removes all need for any reference answers, with no downsides']::text[],0,ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::int[],'LLM judges exhibit systematic biases, such as preferring verbose or self-assured responses, which can distort evaluation results.','LLM judges exhibit systematic biases, such as preferring verbose or self-assured responses, which can distort evaluation results.','Using an LLM as a judge scales evaluation but introduces reliability concerns. Such judges can show position bias, verbosity bias, and a tendency to prefer outputs that resemble their own style. Calibrating with human-labeled examples, randomizing answer order, and using clear rubrics help mitigate these biases.','Using an LLM as a judge scales evaluation but introduces reliability concerns. Such judges can show position bias, verbosity bias, and a tendency to prefer outputs that resemble their own style. Calibrating with human-labeled examples, randomizing answer order, and using clear rubrics help mitigate these biases.',25,'approved','curated-bank');
INSERT INTO "BankQuestion" ("id","skillId","subareaKey","concept","difficulty","type","questionEn","questionPl","optionsEn","optionsPl","correctIndex","acceptedAnswers","orderItems","correctOrder","explanationEn","explanationPl","theoryEn","theoryPl","xp","qualityState","model") VALUES ('bank-engineering-mechanics-1','engineering','engineering:mechanics','engineering-mechanics-1','beginner','mcq','A crate sits still on a flat floor. According to Newton''s first law, what is the net force acting on the crate?','A crate sits still on a flat floor. According to Newton''s first law, what is the net force acting on the crate?',ARRAY['Zero','Equal to its weight, pointing down','Equal to its weight, pointing up','Equal to the friction force, pointing sideways']::text[],ARRAY['Zero','Equal to its weight, pointing down','Equal to its weight, pointing up','Equal to the friction force, pointing sideways']::text[],0,ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::int[],'An object at rest has zero acceleration, so by Newton''s first law the net force on it must be zero.','An object at rest has zero acceleration, so by Newton''s first law the net force on it must be zero.','Newton''s first law says an object stays at rest or in uniform motion unless a net force acts on it. When a crate sits still, the downward weight and the upward normal force from the floor are equal and opposite, so they cancel. The net force is the vector sum of all forces, and here that sum is zero.','Newton''s first law says an object stays at rest or in uniform motion unless a net force acts on it. When a crate sits still, the downward weight and the upward normal force from the floor are equal and opposite, so they cancel. The net force is the vector sum of all forces, and here that sum is zero.',10,'approved','curated-taste');
INSERT INTO "BankQuestion" ("id","skillId","subareaKey","concept","difficulty","type","questionEn","questionPl","optionsEn","optionsPl","correctIndex","acceptedAnswers","orderItems","correctOrder","explanationEn","explanationPl","theoryEn","theoryPl","xp","qualityState","model") VALUES ('bank-engineering-mechanics-2','engineering','engineering:mechanics','engineering-mechanics-2','intermediate','mcq','A net force of 12 N is applied to a 4 kg object on a frictionless surface. Using Newton''s second law, what is the object''s acceleration?','A net force of 12 N is applied to a 4 kg object on a frictionless surface. Using Newton''s second law, what is the object''s acceleration?',ARRAY['3 m/s^2','48 m/s^2','8 m/s^2','0.33 m/s^2']::text[],ARRAY['3 m/s^2','48 m/s^2','8 m/s^2','0.33 m/s^2']::text[],0,ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::int[],'Newton''s second law gives a = F/m = 12 N / 4 kg = 3 m/s^2.','Newton''s second law gives a = F/m = 12 N / 4 kg = 3 m/s^2.','Newton''s second law states that net force equals mass times acceleration (F = ma). Rearranged, acceleration is force divided by mass (a = F/m). A larger force produces more acceleration, while a larger mass resists acceleration, which is why heavier objects are harder to speed up.','Newton''s second law states that net force equals mass times acceleration (F = ma). Rearranged, acceleration is force divided by mass (a = F/m). A larger force produces more acceleration, while a larger mass resists acceleration, which is why heavier objects are harder to speed up.',15,'approved','curated-taste');
INSERT INTO "BankQuestion" ("id","skillId","subareaKey","concept","difficulty","type","questionEn","questionPl","optionsEn","optionsPl","correctIndex","acceptedAnswers","orderItems","correctOrder","explanationEn","explanationPl","theoryEn","theoryPl","xp","qualityState","model") VALUES ('bank-engineering-mechanics-3','engineering','engineering:mechanics','engineering-mechanics-3','advanced','mcq','A cable is rated to break at 6000 N and is used to support a static load of 1500 N. What is the factor of safety?','A cable is rated to break at 6000 N and is used to support a static load of 1500 N. What is the factor of safety?',ARRAY['4','0.25','4500','2']::text[],ARRAY['4','0.25','4500','2']::text[],0,ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::int[],'Factor of safety = breaking (ultimate) load / applied load = 6000 N / 1500 N = 4.','Factor of safety = breaking (ultimate) load / applied load = 6000 N / 1500 N = 4.','The factor of safety compares a component''s failure capacity to the load it actually carries, computed as ultimate strength divided by working load. A value greater than 1 means the part can withstand more than is demanded, giving a margin against overloads, defects, and uncertainty. Engineers choose higher factors for critical or unpredictable applications and lower ones where weight or cost matters and conditions are well understood.','The factor of safety compares a component''s failure capacity to the load it actually carries, computed as ultimate strength divided by working load. A value greater than 1 means the part can withstand more than is demanded, giving a margin against overloads, defects, and uncertainty. Engineers choose higher factors for critical or unpredictable applications and lower ones where weight or cost matters and conditions are well understood.',25,'approved','curated-taste');
INSERT INTO "BankQuestion" ("id","skillId","subareaKey","concept","difficulty","type","questionEn","questionPl","optionsEn","optionsPl","correctIndex","acceptedAnswers","orderItems","correctOrder","explanationEn","explanationPl","theoryEn","theoryPl","xp","qualityState","model") VALUES ('bank-engineering-circuits-1','engineering','engineering:circuits','engineering-circuits-1','beginner','mcq','In a simple circuit, a 12 V source drives a current through a 6 ohm resistor. Using Ohm''s law, what current flows?','In a simple circuit, a 12 V source drives a current through a 6 ohm resistor. Using Ohm''s law, what current flows?',ARRAY['2 A','72 A','0.5 A','18 A']::text[],ARRAY['2 A','72 A','0.5 A','18 A']::text[],0,ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::int[],'Ohm''s law gives I = V / R = 12 V / 6 ohm = 2 A.','Ohm''s law gives I = V / R = 12 V / 6 ohm = 2 A.','Ohm''s law relates voltage, current, and resistance as V = IR. Rearranged, current equals voltage divided by resistance (I = V/R). Higher voltage pushes more current, while higher resistance restricts it, much like water pressure and pipe width affect flow.','Ohm''s law relates voltage, current, and resistance as V = IR. Rearranged, current equals voltage divided by resistance (I = V/R). Higher voltage pushes more current, while higher resistance restricts it, much like water pressure and pipe width affect flow.',10,'approved','curated-taste');
INSERT INTO "BankQuestion" ("id","skillId","subareaKey","concept","difficulty","type","questionEn","questionPl","optionsEn","optionsPl","correctIndex","acceptedAnswers","orderItems","correctOrder","explanationEn","explanationPl","theoryEn","theoryPl","xp","qualityState","model") VALUES ('bank-engineering-circuits-2','engineering','engineering:circuits','engineering-circuits-2','intermediate','mcq','Two resistors of 4 ohm and 6 ohm are connected in series across a battery. What is their total resistance?','Two resistors of 4 ohm and 6 ohm are connected in series across a battery. What is their total resistance?',ARRAY['10 ohm','2.4 ohm','24 ohm','5 ohm']::text[],ARRAY['10 ohm','2.4 ohm','24 ohm','5 ohm']::text[],0,ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::int[],'Resistances in series simply add: 4 ohm + 6 ohm = 10 ohm.','Resistances in series simply add: 4 ohm + 6 ohm = 10 ohm.','When resistors are connected in series, the same current flows through each one and their resistances add to give the total. This is because the current must pass through every resistor in turn, so each adds its own opposition. In contrast, resistors in parallel give a total resistance smaller than the smallest individual resistor.','When resistors are connected in series, the same current flows through each one and their resistances add to give the total. This is because the current must pass through every resistor in turn, so each adds its own opposition. In contrast, resistors in parallel give a total resistance smaller than the smallest individual resistor.',15,'approved','curated-taste');
INSERT INTO "BankQuestion" ("id","skillId","subareaKey","concept","difficulty","type","questionEn","questionPl","optionsEn","optionsPl","correctIndex","acceptedAnswers","orderItems","correctOrder","explanationEn","explanationPl","theoryEn","theoryPl","xp","qualityState","model") VALUES ('bank-engineering-circuits-3','engineering','engineering:circuits','engineering-circuits-3','advanced','mcq','A resistor carries 0.5 A of current with 8 V across it. Using P = VI, how much power does it dissipate?','A resistor carries 0.5 A of current with 8 V across it. Using P = VI, how much power does it dissipate?',ARRAY['4 W','16 W','8.5 W','0.0625 W']::text[],ARRAY['4 W','16 W','8.5 W','0.0625 W']::text[],0,ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::int[],'Power equals voltage times current: P = VI = 8 V x 0.5 A = 4 W.','Power equals voltage times current: P = VI = 8 V x 0.5 A = 4 W.','Electrical power is the rate at which energy is delivered or dissipated, given by P = VI for a component. For a resistor this energy turns into heat, which is why resistors and wires warm up under load. Using Ohm''s law you can also write this as P = I^2 R or P = V^2 / R, which all give the same result.','Electrical power is the rate at which energy is delivered or dissipated, given by P = VI for a component. For a resistor this energy turns into heat, which is why resistors and wires warm up under load. Using Ohm''s law you can also write this as P = I^2 R or P = V^2 / R, which all give the same result.',25,'approved','curated-taste');
INSERT INTO "BankQuestion" ("id","skillId","subareaKey","concept","difficulty","type","questionEn","questionPl","optionsEn","optionsPl","correctIndex","acceptedAnswers","orderItems","correctOrder","explanationEn","explanationPl","theoryEn","theoryPl","xp","qualityState","model") VALUES ('bank-engineering-algorithms-1','engineering','engineering:algorithms','engineering-algorithms-1','beginner','truefalse','A linear search scans a list one element at a time from the start until it finds the target or reaches the end. Its worst-case time complexity is O(n).','A linear search scans a list one element at a time from the start until it finds the target or reaches the end. Its worst-case time complexity is O(n).',ARRAY['True','False']::text[],ARRAY['True','False']::text[],0,ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::int[],'In the worst case the target is last or absent, so a linear search must check all n elements, giving O(n).','In the worst case the target is last or absent, so a linear search must check all n elements, giving O(n).','Big-O notation describes how an algorithm''s running time grows as the input size n increases, focusing on the dominant term. Linear search examines each element once, so in the worst case it does work proportional to n, written O(n). Algorithms that grow more slowly, like O(log n), become much faster than linear search for large inputs.','Big-O notation describes how an algorithm''s running time grows as the input size n increases, focusing on the dominant term. Linear search examines each element once, so in the worst case it does work proportional to n, written O(n). Algorithms that grow more slowly, like O(log n), become much faster than linear search for large inputs.',10,'approved','curated-taste');
INSERT INTO "BankQuestion" ("id","skillId","subareaKey","concept","difficulty","type","questionEn","questionPl","optionsEn","optionsPl","correctIndex","acceptedAnswers","orderItems","correctOrder","explanationEn","explanationPl","theoryEn","theoryPl","xp","qualityState","model") VALUES ('bank-engineering-algorithms-2','engineering','engineering:algorithms','engineering-algorithms-2','intermediate','mcq','What is the worst-case time complexity of binary search on a sorted array of n elements?','What is the worst-case time complexity of binary search on a sorted array of n elements?',ARRAY['O(log n)','O(n)','O(n log n)','O(1)']::text[],ARRAY['O(log n)','O(n)','O(n log n)','O(1)']::text[],0,ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::int[],'Binary search halves the remaining range each step, so it takes about log base 2 of n comparisons, giving O(log n).','Binary search halves the remaining range each step, so it takes about log base 2 of n comparisons, giving O(log n).','Binary search works only on sorted data and repeatedly compares the target to the middle element, discarding half the remaining elements each time. Because the search space halves every step, the number of comparisons grows like the logarithm of n. This makes it dramatically faster than linear search for large sorted collections.','Binary search works only on sorted data and repeatedly compares the target to the middle element, discarding half the remaining elements each time. Because the search space halves every step, the number of comparisons grows like the logarithm of n. This makes it dramatically faster than linear search for large sorted collections.',15,'approved','curated-taste');
INSERT INTO "BankQuestion" ("id","skillId","subareaKey","concept","difficulty","type","questionEn","questionPl","optionsEn","optionsPl","correctIndex","acceptedAnswers","orderItems","correctOrder","explanationEn","explanationPl","theoryEn","theoryPl","xp","qualityState","model") VALUES ('bank-engineering-algorithms-3','engineering','engineering:algorithms','engineering-algorithms-3','advanced','mcq','An algorithm uses two nested loops, each iterating over all n elements of an input, doing constant work inside. What is its time complexity?','An algorithm uses two nested loops, each iterating over all n elements of an input, doing constant work inside. What is its time complexity?',ARRAY['O(n^2)','O(n)','O(2n)','O(log n)']::text[],ARRAY['O(n^2)','O(n)','O(2n)','O(log n)']::text[],0,ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::int[],'An inner loop of n iterations runs for each of the n outer iterations, giving n x n = n^2 operations, or O(n^2).','An inner loop of n iterations runs for each of the n outer iterations, giving n x n = n^2 operations, or O(n^2).','Nested loops multiply their iteration counts, so two loops each running n times perform on the order of n^2 operations. Quadratic algorithms scale poorly: doubling the input roughly quadruples the work. Recognizing nested-loop patterns helps engineers spot performance bottlenecks and seek more efficient approaches for large inputs.','Nested loops multiply their iteration counts, so two loops each running n times perform on the order of n^2 operations. Quadratic algorithms scale poorly: doubling the input roughly quadruples the work. Recognizing nested-loop patterns helps engineers spot performance bottlenecks and seek more efficient approaches for large inputs.',25,'approved','curated-taste');
INSERT INTO "BankQuestion" ("id","skillId","subareaKey","concept","difficulty","type","questionEn","questionPl","optionsEn","optionsPl","correctIndex","acceptedAnswers","orderItems","correctOrder","explanationEn","explanationPl","theoryEn","theoryPl","xp","qualityState","model") VALUES ('bank-engineering-reliability-1','engineering','engineering:reliability','engineering-reliability-1','beginner','mcq','In SI units, which unit measures force?','In SI units, which unit measures force?',ARRAY['Newton','Joule','Watt','Pascal']::text[],ARRAY['Newton','Joule','Watt','Pascal']::text[],0,ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::int[],'The newton (N) is the SI unit of force, defined as the force that accelerates 1 kg at 1 m/s^2.','The newton (N) is the SI unit of force, defined as the force that accelerates 1 kg at 1 m/s^2.','The International System of Units (SI) defines standard units so engineers worldwide can communicate measurements unambiguously. The newton measures force, the joule measures energy, the watt measures power, and the pascal measures pressure. Each derived unit is built from the base units like the kilogram, meter, and second.','The International System of Units (SI) defines standard units so engineers worldwide can communicate measurements unambiguously. The newton measures force, the joule measures energy, the watt measures power, and the pascal measures pressure. Each derived unit is built from the base units like the kilogram, meter, and second.',10,'approved','curated-taste');
INSERT INTO "BankQuestion" ("id","skillId","subareaKey","concept","difficulty","type","questionEn","questionPl","optionsEn","optionsPl","correctIndex","acceptedAnswers","orderItems","correctOrder","explanationEn","explanationPl","theoryEn","theoryPl","xp","qualityState","model") VALUES ('bank-engineering-reliability-2','engineering','engineering:reliability','engineering-reliability-2','intermediate','mcq','A service is available 99% of the time over a 30-day month. Approximately how much total downtime does that allow?','A service is available 99% of the time over a 30-day month. Approximately how much total downtime does that allow?',ARRAY['About 7.2 hours','About 43 minutes','About 3 days','About 22 minutes']::text[],ARRAY['About 7.2 hours','About 43 minutes','About 3 days','About 22 minutes']::text[],0,ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::int[],'A 30-day month is 720 hours, and 1% of 720 hours is 7.2 hours of allowed downtime.','A 30-day month is 720 hours, and 1% of 720 hours is 7.2 hours of allowed downtime.','Availability is the fraction of time a system is operational, often quoted as a percentage like 99% (''two nines''). Downtime is the remaining fraction multiplied by the total time period. Adding more nines shrinks allowed downtime sharply: 99.9% over the same 30 days allows only about 43 minutes.','Availability is the fraction of time a system is operational, often quoted as a percentage like 99% (''two nines''). Downtime is the remaining fraction multiplied by the total time period. Adding more nines shrinks allowed downtime sharply: 99.9% over the same 30 days allows only about 43 minutes.',15,'approved','curated-taste');
INSERT INTO "BankQuestion" ("id","skillId","subareaKey","concept","difficulty","type","questionEn","questionPl","optionsEn","optionsPl","correctIndex","acceptedAnswers","orderItems","correctOrder","explanationEn","explanationPl","theoryEn","theoryPl","xp","qualityState","model") VALUES ('bank-engineering-reliability-3','engineering','engineering:reliability','engineering-reliability-3','advanced','mcq','Two independent components are in series, each with a reliability (probability of working) of 0.9. What is the overall reliability of the system?','Two independent components are in series, each with a reliability (probability of working) of 0.9. What is the overall reliability of the system?',ARRAY['0.81','0.9','0.99','1.8']::text[],ARRAY['0.81','0.9','0.99','1.8']::text[],0,ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::int[],'For independent components in series, reliabilities multiply: 0.9 x 0.9 = 0.81.','For independent components in series, reliabilities multiply: 0.9 x 0.9 = 0.81.','In a series reliability model, the system works only if every component works, so the overall reliability is the product of the individual reliabilities. Because each value is less than 1, adding more series components always lowers total reliability. Designers improve reliability by adding redundancy in parallel, where the system survives as long as at least one path works.','In a series reliability model, the system works only if every component works, so the overall reliability is the product of the individual reliabilities. Because each value is less than 1, adding more series components always lowers total reliability. Designers improve reliability by adding redundancy in parallel, where the system survives as long as at least one path works.',25,'approved','curated-taste');
INSERT INTO "BankQuestion" ("id","skillId","subareaKey","concept","difficulty","type","questionEn","questionPl","optionsEn","optionsPl","correctIndex","acceptedAnswers","orderItems","correctOrder","explanationEn","explanationPl","theoryEn","theoryPl","xp","qualityState","model") VALUES ('bankq-engineering-mechanics-b-1','engineering','engineering:mechanics','engineering-mechanics-b-1','beginner','mcq','A constant net force of 10 N acts on a 2 kg cart on a frictionless surface. Using Newton''s second law (F = m * a), what is the cart''s acceleration?','A constant net force of 10 N acts on a 2 kg cart on a frictionless surface. Using Newton''s second law (F = m * a), what is the cart''s acceleration?',ARRAY['5 m/s^2','20 m/s^2','0.2 m/s^2','12 m/s^2']::text[],ARRAY['5 m/s^2','20 m/s^2','0.2 m/s^2','12 m/s^2']::text[],0,ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::int[],'Acceleration is force divided by mass, so a = 10 N / 2 kg = 5 m/s^2.','Acceleration is force divided by mass, so a = 10 N / 2 kg = 5 m/s^2.','Newton''s second law states that net force equals mass times acceleration (F = m * a). Solving for acceleration gives a = F / m. The unit newton is defined so that 1 N accelerates 1 kg at 1 m/s^2.','Newton''s second law states that net force equals mass times acceleration (F = m * a). Solving for acceleration gives a = F / m. The unit newton is defined so that 1 N accelerates 1 kg at 1 m/s^2.',10,'approved','curated-bank');
INSERT INTO "BankQuestion" ("id","skillId","subareaKey","concept","difficulty","type","questionEn","questionPl","optionsEn","optionsPl","correctIndex","acceptedAnswers","orderItems","correctOrder","explanationEn","explanationPl","theoryEn","theoryPl","xp","qualityState","model") VALUES ('bankq-engineering-mechanics-b-2','engineering','engineering:mechanics','engineering-mechanics-b-2','beginner','truefalse','True or false: The weight of an object equals its mass multiplied by the local gravitational acceleration g.','True or false: The weight of an object equals its mass multiplied by the local gravitational acceleration g.',ARRAY['True','False']::text[],ARRAY['True','False']::text[],0,ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::int[],'Weight is the gravitational force on a mass, given by W = m * g.','Weight is the gravitational force on a mass, given by W = m * g.','Mass is the amount of matter in an object and is the same everywhere. Weight is a force caused by gravity acting on that mass, calculated as W = m * g. On Earth g is about 9.81 m/s^2, so a 1 kg mass weighs about 9.81 N.','Mass is the amount of matter in an object and is the same everywhere. Weight is a force caused by gravity acting on that mass, calculated as W = m * g. On Earth g is about 9.81 m/s^2, so a 1 kg mass weighs about 9.81 N.',10,'approved','curated-bank');
INSERT INTO "BankQuestion" ("id","skillId","subareaKey","concept","difficulty","type","questionEn","questionPl","optionsEn","optionsPl","correctIndex","acceptedAnswers","orderItems","correctOrder","explanationEn","explanationPl","theoryEn","theoryPl","xp","qualityState","model") VALUES ('bankq-engineering-mechanics-i-1','engineering','engineering:mechanics','engineering-mechanics-i-1','intermediate','mcq','A force of 20 N is applied at the end of a wrench 0.25 m long, perpendicular to the handle. What torque does it produce about the bolt?','A force of 20 N is applied at the end of a wrench 0.25 m long, perpendicular to the handle. What torque does it produce about the bolt?',ARRAY['5 N*m','80 N*m','0.0125 N*m','20.25 N*m']::text[],ARRAY['5 N*m','80 N*m','0.0125 N*m','20.25 N*m']::text[],0,ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::int[],'Torque equals force times perpendicular lever arm, so 20 N * 0.25 m = 5 N*m.','Torque equals force times perpendicular lever arm, so 20 N * 0.25 m = 5 N*m.','Torque is the rotational effect of a force, calculated as the force multiplied by the perpendicular distance from the pivot (tau = F * r). It is measured in newton-meters. A longer lever arm produces more torque for the same applied force.','Torque is the rotational effect of a force, calculated as the force multiplied by the perpendicular distance from the pivot (tau = F * r). It is measured in newton-meters. A longer lever arm produces more torque for the same applied force.',15,'approved','curated-bank');
INSERT INTO "BankQuestion" ("id","skillId","subareaKey","concept","difficulty","type","questionEn","questionPl","optionsEn","optionsPl","correctIndex","acceptedAnswers","orderItems","correctOrder","explanationEn","explanationPl","theoryEn","theoryPl","xp","qualityState","model") VALUES ('bankq-engineering-mechanics-i-2','engineering','engineering:mechanics','engineering-mechanics-i-2','intermediate','mcq','A 4 kg object moves at 3 m/s. What is its kinetic energy, using KE = (1/2) * m * v^2?','A 4 kg object moves at 3 m/s. What is its kinetic energy, using KE = (1/2) * m * v^2?',ARRAY['18 J','36 J','12 J','6 J']::text[],ARRAY['18 J','36 J','12 J','6 J']::text[],0,ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::int[],'KE = 0.5 * 4 kg * (3 m/s)^2 = 0.5 * 4 * 9 = 18 J.','KE = 0.5 * 4 kg * (3 m/s)^2 = 0.5 * 4 * 9 = 18 J.','Kinetic energy is the energy of motion, given by KE = (1/2) * m * v^2. Because velocity is squared, doubling the speed quadruples the kinetic energy. Energy is measured in joules (J), where 1 J = 1 kg*m^2/s^2.','Kinetic energy is the energy of motion, given by KE = (1/2) * m * v^2. Because velocity is squared, doubling the speed quadruples the kinetic energy. Energy is measured in joules (J), where 1 J = 1 kg*m^2/s^2.',15,'approved','curated-bank');
INSERT INTO "BankQuestion" ("id","skillId","subareaKey","concept","difficulty","type","questionEn","questionPl","optionsEn","optionsPl","correctIndex","acceptedAnswers","orderItems","correctOrder","explanationEn","explanationPl","theoryEn","theoryPl","xp","qualityState","model") VALUES ('bankq-engineering-mechanics-a-1','engineering','engineering:mechanics','engineering-mechanics-a-1','advanced','mcq','A steel rod can withstand a maximum (ultimate) tensile stress of 400 MPa. If the working stress in service is 100 MPa, what is the factor of safety?','A steel rod can withstand a maximum (ultimate) tensile stress of 400 MPa. If the working stress in service is 100 MPa, what is the factor of safety?',ARRAY['4','0.25','300','40']::text[],ARRAY['4','0.25','300','40']::text[],0,ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::int[],'Factor of safety is ultimate stress divided by working stress, so 400 MPa / 100 MPa = 4.','Factor of safety is ultimate stress divided by working stress, so 400 MPa / 100 MPa = 4.','The factor of safety is the ratio of a material''s failure strength to the actual stress it experiences in use. A value greater than 1 means the design has margin before failure. Engineers pick larger factors when loads are uncertain or failure would be dangerous.','The factor of safety is the ratio of a material''s failure strength to the actual stress it experiences in use. A value greater than 1 means the design has margin before failure. Engineers pick larger factors when loads are uncertain or failure would be dangerous.',25,'approved','curated-bank');
INSERT INTO "BankQuestion" ("id","skillId","subareaKey","concept","difficulty","type","questionEn","questionPl","optionsEn","optionsPl","correctIndex","acceptedAnswers","orderItems","correctOrder","explanationEn","explanationPl","theoryEn","theoryPl","xp","qualityState","model") VALUES ('bankq-engineering-mechanics-a-2','engineering','engineering:mechanics','engineering-mechanics-a-2','advanced','mcq','A simply supported beam carries a single central point load of 600 N over a span of 4 m. What is the maximum bending moment at the center, given M = (P * L) / 4?','A simply supported beam carries a single central point load of 600 N over a span of 4 m. What is the maximum bending moment at the center, given M = (P * L) / 4?',ARRAY['600 N*m','2400 N*m','150 N*m','300 N*m']::text[],ARRAY['600 N*m','2400 N*m','150 N*m','300 N*m']::text[],0,ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::int[],'M = (P * L) / 4 = (600 N * 4 m) / 4 = 600 N*m.','M = (P * L) / 4 = (600 N * 4 m) / 4 = 600 N*m.','For a simply supported beam with a central point load, the maximum bending moment occurs at midspan and equals (P * L) / 4. Bending moment measures the internal turning effect that tends to bend the beam. It is largest where the beam is most likely to fail in bending.','For a simply supported beam with a central point load, the maximum bending moment occurs at midspan and equals (P * L) / 4. Bending moment measures the internal turning effect that tends to bend the beam. It is largest where the beam is most likely to fail in bending.',25,'approved','curated-bank');
INSERT INTO "BankQuestion" ("id","skillId","subareaKey","concept","difficulty","type","questionEn","questionPl","optionsEn","optionsPl","correctIndex","acceptedAnswers","orderItems","correctOrder","explanationEn","explanationPl","theoryEn","theoryPl","xp","qualityState","model") VALUES ('bankq-engineering-circuits-b-1','engineering','engineering:circuits','engineering-circuits-b-1','beginner','mcq','A 12 V battery is connected across a 4 ohm resistor. Using Ohm''s law (V = I * R), what current flows through the resistor?','A 12 V battery is connected across a 4 ohm resistor. Using Ohm''s law (V = I * R), what current flows through the resistor?',ARRAY['3 A','48 A','0.33 A','16 A']::text[],ARRAY['3 A','48 A','0.33 A','16 A']::text[],0,ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::int[],'Current is voltage divided by resistance, so I = 12 V / 4 ohm = 3 A.','Current is voltage divided by resistance, so I = 12 V / 4 ohm = 3 A.','Ohm''s law relates voltage, current, and resistance as V = I * R. Rearranged, current equals voltage divided by resistance (I = V / R). For a fixed voltage, a smaller resistance allows a larger current to flow.','Ohm''s law relates voltage, current, and resistance as V = I * R. Rearranged, current equals voltage divided by resistance (I = V / R). For a fixed voltage, a smaller resistance allows a larger current to flow.',10,'approved','curated-bank');
INSERT INTO "BankQuestion" ("id","skillId","subareaKey","concept","difficulty","type","questionEn","questionPl","optionsEn","optionsPl","correctIndex","acceptedAnswers","orderItems","correctOrder","explanationEn","explanationPl","theoryEn","theoryPl","xp","qualityState","model") VALUES ('bankq-engineering-circuits-b-2','engineering','engineering:circuits','engineering-circuits-b-2','beginner','truefalse','True or false: In a series circuit, the same current flows through every component.','True or false: In a series circuit, the same current flows through every component.',ARRAY['True','False']::text[],ARRAY['True','False']::text[],0,ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::int[],'A series circuit provides a single path, so the current is identical through all components.','A series circuit provides a single path, so the current is identical through all components.','In a series circuit, components are connected end to end forming one path for current. Because there is only one path, the current is the same everywhere in the loop. The supply voltage divides across the components in proportion to their resistances.','In a series circuit, components are connected end to end forming one path for current. Because there is only one path, the current is the same everywhere in the loop. The supply voltage divides across the components in proportion to their resistances.',10,'approved','curated-bank');
INSERT INTO "BankQuestion" ("id","skillId","subareaKey","concept","difficulty","type","questionEn","questionPl","optionsEn","optionsPl","correctIndex","acceptedAnswers","orderItems","correctOrder","explanationEn","explanationPl","theoryEn","theoryPl","xp","qualityState","model") VALUES ('bankq-engineering-circuits-i-1','engineering','engineering:circuits','engineering-circuits-i-1','intermediate','mcq','Two resistors of 6 ohm and 3 ohm are connected in parallel. What is their equivalent resistance?','Two resistors of 6 ohm and 3 ohm are connected in parallel. What is their equivalent resistance?',ARRAY['2 ohm','9 ohm','4.5 ohm','18 ohm']::text[],ARRAY['2 ohm','9 ohm','4.5 ohm','18 ohm']::text[],0,ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::int[],'For parallel resistors, 1/R = 1/6 + 1/3 = 1/2, so R = 2 ohm.','For parallel resistors, 1/R = 1/6 + 1/3 = 1/2, so R = 2 ohm.','Resistors in parallel share the same voltage but split the current. The equivalent resistance is found from 1/R = 1/R1 + 1/R2. The result is always smaller than the smallest individual resistor because there are more paths for current.','Resistors in parallel share the same voltage but split the current. The equivalent resistance is found from 1/R = 1/R1 + 1/R2. The result is always smaller than the smallest individual resistor because there are more paths for current.',15,'approved','curated-bank');
INSERT INTO "BankQuestion" ("id","skillId","subareaKey","concept","difficulty","type","questionEn","questionPl","optionsEn","optionsPl","correctIndex","acceptedAnswers","orderItems","correctOrder","explanationEn","explanationPl","theoryEn","theoryPl","xp","qualityState","model") VALUES ('bankq-engineering-circuits-i-2','engineering','engineering:circuits','engineering-circuits-i-2','intermediate','mcq','A device draws 2 A at 120 V. What is its power consumption, using P = V * I?','A device draws 2 A at 120 V. What is its power consumption, using P = V * I?',ARRAY['240 W','60 W','122 W','480 W']::text[],ARRAY['240 W','60 W','122 W','480 W']::text[],0,ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::int[],'Power equals voltage times current, so P = 120 V * 2 A = 240 W.','Power equals voltage times current, so P = 120 V * 2 A = 240 W.','Electrical power is the rate of energy use, given by P = V * I. It is measured in watts, where 1 W = 1 J/s. Combined with Ohm''s law, power can also be written as P = I^2 * R or P = V^2 / R.','Electrical power is the rate of energy use, given by P = V * I. It is measured in watts, where 1 W = 1 J/s. Combined with Ohm''s law, power can also be written as P = I^2 * R or P = V^2 / R.',15,'approved','curated-bank');
INSERT INTO "BankQuestion" ("id","skillId","subareaKey","concept","difficulty","type","questionEn","questionPl","optionsEn","optionsPl","correctIndex","acceptedAnswers","orderItems","correctOrder","explanationEn","explanationPl","theoryEn","theoryPl","xp","qualityState","model") VALUES ('bankq-engineering-circuits-a-1','engineering','engineering:circuits','engineering-circuits-a-1','advanced','mcq','An RC circuit has R = 10 kohm and C = 100 uF. What is its time constant (tau = R * C)?','An RC circuit has R = 10 kohm and C = 100 uF. What is its time constant (tau = R * C)?',ARRAY['1 s','0.1 s','10 s','0.001 s']::text[],ARRAY['1 s','0.1 s','10 s','0.001 s']::text[],0,ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::int[],'tau = R * C = 10000 ohm * 0.0001 F = 1 s.','tau = R * C = 10000 ohm * 0.0001 F = 1 s.','The time constant of an RC circuit is tau = R * C and sets how fast a capacitor charges or discharges. After one time constant the capacitor reaches about 63 percent of its final voltage. Using SI units (ohms and farads) gives the result directly in seconds.','The time constant of an RC circuit is tau = R * C and sets how fast a capacitor charges or discharges. After one time constant the capacitor reaches about 63 percent of its final voltage. Using SI units (ohms and farads) gives the result directly in seconds.',25,'approved','curated-bank');
INSERT INTO "BankQuestion" ("id","skillId","subareaKey","concept","difficulty","type","questionEn","questionPl","optionsEn","optionsPl","correctIndex","acceptedAnswers","orderItems","correctOrder","explanationEn","explanationPl","theoryEn","theoryPl","xp","qualityState","model") VALUES ('bankq-engineering-circuits-a-2','engineering','engineering:circuits','engineering-circuits-a-2','advanced','mcq','A resistor carries 0.5 A and has 8 ohm of resistance. Using P = I^2 * R, how much power does it dissipate as heat?','A resistor carries 0.5 A and has 8 ohm of resistance. Using P = I^2 * R, how much power does it dissipate as heat?',ARRAY['2 W','4 W','16 W','0.25 W']::text[],ARRAY['2 W','4 W','16 W','0.25 W']::text[],0,ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::int[],'P = I^2 * R = (0.5)^2 * 8 = 0.25 * 8 = 2 W.','P = I^2 * R = (0.5)^2 * 8 = 0.25 * 8 = 2 W.','Power dissipated in a resistor can be computed as P = I^2 * R, which follows from combining P = V * I with Ohm''s law V = I * R. This heat-generating loss is called Joule heating. Because current is squared, doubling the current quadruples the dissipated power.','Power dissipated in a resistor can be computed as P = I^2 * R, which follows from combining P = V * I with Ohm''s law V = I * R. This heat-generating loss is called Joule heating. Because current is squared, doubling the current quadruples the dissipated power.',25,'approved','curated-bank');
INSERT INTO "BankQuestion" ("id","skillId","subareaKey","concept","difficulty","type","questionEn","questionPl","optionsEn","optionsPl","correctIndex","acceptedAnswers","orderItems","correctOrder","explanationEn","explanationPl","theoryEn","theoryPl","xp","qualityState","model") VALUES ('bankq-engineering-algorithms-b-1','engineering','engineering:algorithms','engineering-algorithms-b-1','beginner','mcq','What is the time complexity of a linear search through an unsorted array of n elements in the worst case?','What is the time complexity of a linear search through an unsorted array of n elements in the worst case?',ARRAY['O(n)','O(1)','O(log n)','O(n^2)']::text[],ARRAY['O(n)','O(1)','O(log n)','O(n^2)']::text[],0,ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::int[],'In the worst case linear search checks every one of the n elements, giving O(n).','In the worst case linear search checks every one of the n elements, giving O(n).','Linear search scans elements one by one until it finds the target or reaches the end. In the worst case the target is last or absent, requiring all n comparisons. This makes its time complexity O(n), meaning runtime grows in proportion to the input size.','Linear search scans elements one by one until it finds the target or reaches the end. In the worst case the target is last or absent, requiring all n comparisons. This makes its time complexity O(n), meaning runtime grows in proportion to the input size.',10,'approved','curated-bank');
INSERT INTO "BankQuestion" ("id","skillId","subareaKey","concept","difficulty","type","questionEn","questionPl","optionsEn","optionsPl","correctIndex","acceptedAnswers","orderItems","correctOrder","explanationEn","explanationPl","theoryEn","theoryPl","xp","qualityState","model") VALUES ('bankq-engineering-algorithms-b-2','engineering','engineering:algorithms','engineering-algorithms-b-2','beginner','truefalse','True or false: Binary search requires the input array to be sorted beforehand.','True or false: Binary search requires the input array to be sorted beforehand.',ARRAY['True','False']::text[],ARRAY['True','False']::text[],0,ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::int[],'Binary search relies on order to discard half the search space each step, so the data must be sorted.','Binary search relies on order to discard half the search space each step, so the data must be sorted.','Binary search repeatedly compares the target to the middle element and eliminates half of the remaining elements. This halving only works if the array is sorted so that the discarded half cannot contain the target. Its time complexity is O(log n).','Binary search repeatedly compares the target to the middle element and eliminates half of the remaining elements. This halving only works if the array is sorted so that the discarded half cannot contain the target. Its time complexity is O(log n).',10,'approved','curated-bank');
INSERT INTO "BankQuestion" ("id","skillId","subareaKey","concept","difficulty","type","questionEn","questionPl","optionsEn","optionsPl","correctIndex","acceptedAnswers","orderItems","correctOrder","explanationEn","explanationPl","theoryEn","theoryPl","xp","qualityState","model") VALUES ('bankq-engineering-algorithms-i-1','engineering','engineering:algorithms','engineering-algorithms-i-1','intermediate','mcq','What is the average and worst-case time complexity of binary search on a sorted array of n elements?','What is the average and worst-case time complexity of binary search on a sorted array of n elements?',ARRAY['O(log n)','O(n)','O(1)','O(n log n)']::text[],ARRAY['O(log n)','O(n)','O(1)','O(n log n)']::text[],0,ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::int[],'Binary search halves the search space each step, so it takes about log base 2 of n steps, giving O(log n).','Binary search halves the search space each step, so it takes about log base 2 of n steps, giving O(log n).','Each comparison in binary search removes half of the remaining candidates. The number of halvings needed to reduce n elements to one is log base 2 of n. Therefore both the average and worst-case time complexity is O(log n).','Each comparison in binary search removes half of the remaining candidates. The number of halvings needed to reduce n elements to one is log base 2 of n. Therefore both the average and worst-case time complexity is O(log n).',15,'approved','curated-bank');
INSERT INTO "BankQuestion" ("id","skillId","subareaKey","concept","difficulty","type","questionEn","questionPl","optionsEn","optionsPl","correctIndex","acceptedAnswers","orderItems","correctOrder","explanationEn","explanationPl","theoryEn","theoryPl","xp","qualityState","model") VALUES ('bankq-engineering-algorithms-i-2','engineering','engineering:algorithms','engineering-algorithms-i-2','intermediate','mcq','Which data structure follows Last-In First-Out (LIFO) order, where the most recently added item is removed first?','Which data structure follows Last-In First-Out (LIFO) order, where the most recently added item is removed first?',ARRAY['Stack','Queue','Linked list','Hash table']::text[],ARRAY['Stack','Queue','Linked list','Hash table']::text[],0,ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::int[],'A stack adds and removes elements at the same end, so the last item pushed is the first popped.','A stack adds and removes elements at the same end, so the last item pushed is the first popped.','A stack is a linear data structure with push and pop operations at one end, giving Last-In First-Out behavior. A queue, by contrast, is First-In First-Out. Stacks are used for function call management, undo features, and expression evaluation.','A stack is a linear data structure with push and pop operations at one end, giving Last-In First-Out behavior. A queue, by contrast, is First-In First-Out. Stacks are used for function call management, undo features, and expression evaluation.',15,'approved','curated-bank');
INSERT INTO "BankQuestion" ("id","skillId","subareaKey","concept","difficulty","type","questionEn","questionPl","optionsEn","optionsPl","correctIndex","acceptedAnswers","orderItems","correctOrder","explanationEn","explanationPl","theoryEn","theoryPl","xp","qualityState","model") VALUES ('bankq-engineering-algorithms-a-1','engineering','engineering:algorithms','engineering-algorithms-a-1','advanced','mcq','What is the average-case time complexity of the merge sort algorithm when sorting n elements?','What is the average-case time complexity of the merge sort algorithm when sorting n elements?',ARRAY['O(n log n)','O(n^2)','O(n)','O(log n)']::text[],ARRAY['O(n log n)','O(n^2)','O(n)','O(log n)']::text[],0,ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::int[],'Merge sort splits into log n levels and does O(n) work merging at each level, giving O(n log n).','Merge sort splits into log n levels and does O(n) work merging at each level, giving O(n log n).','Merge sort recursively divides the array in half until single elements remain, then merges sorted halves. There are about log base 2 of n levels of division, and each level requires O(n) work to merge. The total is O(n log n) in the best, average, and worst cases.','Merge sort recursively divides the array in half until single elements remain, then merges sorted halves. There are about log base 2 of n levels of division, and each level requires O(n) work to merge. The total is O(n log n) in the best, average, and worst cases.',25,'approved','curated-bank');
INSERT INTO "BankQuestion" ("id","skillId","subareaKey","concept","difficulty","type","questionEn","questionPl","optionsEn","optionsPl","correctIndex","acceptedAnswers","orderItems","correctOrder","explanationEn","explanationPl","theoryEn","theoryPl","xp","qualityState","model") VALUES ('bankq-engineering-algorithms-a-2','engineering','engineering:algorithms','engineering-algorithms-a-2','advanced','mcq','A nested loop iterates j from 0 to n for each i from 0 to n, doing constant work inside. What is the overall time complexity?','A nested loop iterates j from 0 to n for each i from 0 to n, doing constant work inside. What is the overall time complexity?',ARRAY['O(n^2)','O(n)','O(2n)','O(n log n)']::text[],ARRAY['O(n^2)','O(n)','O(2n)','O(n log n)']::text[],0,ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::int[],'The inner loop runs n times for each of the n outer iterations, giving n * n = O(n^2) operations.','The inner loop runs n times for each of the n outer iterations, giving n * n = O(n^2) operations.','When one loop is nested inside another and each runs n times, the total iterations multiply to n^2. Constant work inside the loops does not change the order of growth. This quadratic behavior is written O(n^2) and scales poorly for large n.','When one loop is nested inside another and each runs n times, the total iterations multiply to n^2. Constant work inside the loops does not change the order of growth. This quadratic behavior is written O(n^2) and scales poorly for large n.',25,'approved','curated-bank');
INSERT INTO "BankQuestion" ("id","skillId","subareaKey","concept","difficulty","type","questionEn","questionPl","optionsEn","optionsPl","correctIndex","acceptedAnswers","orderItems","correctOrder","explanationEn","explanationPl","theoryEn","theoryPl","xp","qualityState","model") VALUES ('bankq-engineering-reliability-b-1','engineering','engineering:reliability','engineering-reliability-b-1','beginner','mcq','How many milliamperes (mA) are in 2.5 amperes (A)?','How many milliamperes (mA) are in 2.5 amperes (A)?',ARRAY['2500 mA','250 mA','25 mA','0.0025 mA']::text[],ARRAY['2500 mA','250 mA','25 mA','0.0025 mA']::text[],0,ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::int[],'The prefix milli means one-thousandth, so 2.5 A * 1000 = 2500 mA.','The prefix milli means one-thousandth, so 2.5 A * 1000 = 2500 mA.','SI prefixes scale base units by powers of ten. The prefix milli (m) means one-thousandth, so 1 A equals 1000 mA. To convert from amperes to milliamperes you multiply by 1000.','SI prefixes scale base units by powers of ten. The prefix milli (m) means one-thousandth, so 1 A equals 1000 mA. To convert from amperes to milliamperes you multiply by 1000.',10,'approved','curated-bank');
INSERT INTO "BankQuestion" ("id","skillId","subareaKey","concept","difficulty","type","questionEn","questionPl","optionsEn","optionsPl","correctIndex","acceptedAnswers","orderItems","correctOrder","explanationEn","explanationPl","theoryEn","theoryPl","xp","qualityState","model") VALUES ('bankq-engineering-reliability-b-2','engineering','engineering:reliability','engineering-reliability-b-2','beginner','truefalse','True or false: One kilometer equals 1000 meters.','True or false: One kilometer equals 1000 meters.',ARRAY['True','False']::text[],ARRAY['True','False']::text[],0,ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::int[],'The prefix kilo means one thousand, so 1 km = 1000 m.','The prefix kilo means one thousand, so 1 km = 1000 m.','In the SI system the prefix kilo (k) multiplies a base unit by one thousand. Thus one kilometer is 1000 meters and one kilogram is 1000 grams. Recognizing prefixes lets you convert between unit scales reliably.','In the SI system the prefix kilo (k) multiplies a base unit by one thousand. Thus one kilometer is 1000 meters and one kilogram is 1000 grams. Recognizing prefixes lets you convert between unit scales reliably.',10,'approved','curated-bank');
INSERT INTO "BankQuestion" ("id","skillId","subareaKey","concept","difficulty","type","questionEn","questionPl","optionsEn","optionsPl","correctIndex","acceptedAnswers","orderItems","correctOrder","explanationEn","explanationPl","theoryEn","theoryPl","xp","qualityState","model") VALUES ('bankq-engineering-reliability-i-1','engineering','engineering:reliability','engineering-reliability-i-1','intermediate','mcq','A system is available 23.76 hours out of every 24-hour day. What is its availability expressed as a percentage?','A system is available 23.76 hours out of every 24-hour day. What is its availability expressed as a percentage?',ARRAY['99%','90%','97.6%','95%']::text[],ARRAY['99%','90%','97.6%','95%']::text[],0,ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::int[],'Availability = 23.76 / 24 = 0.99, which is 99%.','Availability = 23.76 / 24 = 0.99, which is 99%.','Availability is the fraction of time a system is operational, computed as uptime divided by total time. Multiplying by 100 expresses it as a percentage. A value of 99% corresponds to roughly 0.24 hours (about 14 minutes) of downtime per day.','Availability is the fraction of time a system is operational, computed as uptime divided by total time. Multiplying by 100 expresses it as a percentage. A value of 99% corresponds to roughly 0.24 hours (about 14 minutes) of downtime per day.',15,'approved','curated-bank');
INSERT INTO "BankQuestion" ("id","skillId","subareaKey","concept","difficulty","type","questionEn","questionPl","optionsEn","optionsPl","correctIndex","acceptedAnswers","orderItems","correctOrder","explanationEn","explanationPl","theoryEn","theoryPl","xp","qualityState","model") VALUES ('bankq-engineering-reliability-i-2','engineering','engineering:reliability','engineering-reliability-i-2','intermediate','mcq','Convert a pressure of 2 kilopascals (kPa) to pascals (Pa).','Convert a pressure of 2 kilopascals (kPa) to pascals (Pa).',ARRAY['2000 Pa','200 Pa','20000 Pa','0.002 Pa']::text[],ARRAY['2000 Pa','200 Pa','20000 Pa','0.002 Pa']::text[],0,ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::int[],'The prefix kilo means one thousand, so 2 kPa = 2 * 1000 = 2000 Pa.','The prefix kilo means one thousand, so 2 kPa = 2 * 1000 = 2000 Pa.','The pascal (Pa) is the SI unit of pressure, equal to one newton per square meter. The prefix kilo multiplies by one thousand, so 1 kPa = 1000 Pa. Converting 2 kPa therefore gives 2000 Pa.','The pascal (Pa) is the SI unit of pressure, equal to one newton per square meter. The prefix kilo multiplies by one thousand, so 1 kPa = 1000 Pa. Converting 2 kPa therefore gives 2000 Pa.',15,'approved','curated-bank');
INSERT INTO "BankQuestion" ("id","skillId","subareaKey","concept","difficulty","type","questionEn","questionPl","optionsEn","optionsPl","correctIndex","acceptedAnswers","orderItems","correctOrder","explanationEn","explanationPl","theoryEn","theoryPl","xp","qualityState","model") VALUES ('bankq-engineering-reliability-a-1','engineering','engineering:reliability','engineering-reliability-a-1','advanced','mcq','A service must meet 99.9% availability over a 30-day month (720 hours). What is the maximum allowed downtime?','A service must meet 99.9% availability over a 30-day month (720 hours). What is the maximum allowed downtime?',ARRAY['About 43.2 minutes','About 7.2 hours','About 4.32 minutes','About 72 minutes']::text[],ARRAY['About 43.2 minutes','About 7.2 hours','About 4.32 minutes','About 72 minutes']::text[],0,ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::int[],'Allowed downtime = 0.001 * 720 h = 0.72 h = 43.2 minutes.','Allowed downtime = 0.001 * 720 h = 0.72 h = 43.2 minutes.','Allowed downtime equals the unavailability fraction times the total period. For 99.9% availability the unavailability is 0.1%, or 0.001. Over 720 hours this is 0.72 hours, which is about 43.2 minutes per month.','Allowed downtime equals the unavailability fraction times the total period. For 99.9% availability the unavailability is 0.1%, or 0.001. Over 720 hours this is 0.72 hours, which is about 43.2 minutes per month.',25,'approved','curated-bank');
INSERT INTO "BankQuestion" ("id","skillId","subareaKey","concept","difficulty","type","questionEn","questionPl","optionsEn","optionsPl","correctIndex","acceptedAnswers","orderItems","correctOrder","explanationEn","explanationPl","theoryEn","theoryPl","xp","qualityState","model") VALUES ('bankq-engineering-reliability-a-2','engineering','engineering:reliability','engineering-reliability-a-2','advanced','mcq','A component has a mean time between failures (MTBF) of 1000 hours and a mean time to repair (MTTR) of 10 hours. What is its steady-state availability, using MTBF / (MTBF + MTTR)?','A component has a mean time between failures (MTBF) of 1000 hours and a mean time to repair (MTTR) of 10 hours. What is its steady-state availability, using MTBF / (MTBF + MTTR)?',ARRAY['About 99.0%','About 90.0%','About 99.9%','About 50.0%']::text[],ARRAY['About 99.0%','About 90.0%','About 99.9%','About 50.0%']::text[],0,ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::text[],ARRAY[]::int[],'Availability = 1000 / (1000 + 10) = 1000 / 1010 = 0.990, or about 99.0%.','Availability = 1000 / (1000 + 10) = 1000 / 1010 = 0.990, or about 99.0%.','Steady-state availability is the fraction of time a repairable system is working, given by MTBF / (MTBF + MTTR). MTBF measures how long the system runs between failures and MTTR measures how long repairs take. Increasing MTBF or reducing MTTR raises availability.','Steady-state availability is the fraction of time a repairable system is working, given by MTBF / (MTBF + MTTR). MTBF measures how long the system runs between failures and MTTR measures how long repairs take. Increasing MTBF or reducing MTTR raises availability.',25,'approved','curated-bank');
